<HEADLINE> De Klerk Should Continue Playing Public Role: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela said today it would be in the interest of
nation-building to invite F. W. De Klerk, who recently retired as
National Party leader, to continue playing public role.
</P>
<P>
"As far as I am concerned, and if he agrees, I will use him,"
Mandela told reporters in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
De Klerk should be given "something where he can use his
talent, not as a leader of a political party, but as one of the
most eminent South Africans", Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela did not elaborate on his plan for De Klerk.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for De Klerk said if the former leader of the
National Party received specific requests, including from the
government, he would definitely respond favorably should he find
it practical and possible.
</P>
<P>
When he resigned in late August, De Klerk said he would quit
active politics completely.
</P>
<P>
"However, he (De Klerk) did indicated that he would utilize
all opportunities that were presented to continue playing a
constructive role in the solution of the country's problems and
the international advancement of South Africa's interest," the
spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
