<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian President Sets Guidelines for New Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami has issued a memorandum to various executive departments
of the government, outlining the priorities in compiling next
year's budget, The Persian daily Hamshahri reported today.
</P>
<P>
Khatami highlighted social justice and eradication of poverty
as major considerations in compiling the new budget which will
start from March 21, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Strengthening the national currency, increasing the country's
share in world markets, working toward non-reliance on oil
revenues, elimination of monopolies and preparing grounds for
healthy competitions in the economic scene of the country are
mentioned as some of the major goals of the new government.
</P>
<P>
Khatami also highlighted his government's commitment to
subsidize the basic necessities of the public as well as
providing financial support for cultural organizations which aim
to promote culture and arts in the society.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the new government stresses
continuation and completion of the already started development
programs and in general bans on start of new projects.
</P>
<P>
Strict discipline in using foreign exchange revenues and
limiting the country's imports also figure prominently in the
new government's agenda, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Khatami stressed that the agenda presented during the
presidential campaign and the subsequent sessions of the
Parliament should be given due attention in compiling next
year's budget.
</P>
<P>
The memo touches on the previous government's economic
successes after the eight-year war between Iran and Iraq, before
moving to what it calls "imbalances and shortcomings" facing the
new government.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate has been down to 17 percent this year from
49.4 percent two years ago. A 37 percent annual growth in
government's tax revenues was among the major accomplishments
of the government during the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
Among the major problems facing Khatami's government is
non-realization of the forecast revenues for the current year,
the memo said. But it did not elaborate on the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
