<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright, Arafat Agree on Need to Fight Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RAMALLAH, PALESTINE, September 11 (Xinhua) -- United States
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, currently on a rescue
mission to save the Israeli-Palestinian peace process, obtained a
promise from Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to fight terrorism
here today.
</P>
<P>
After a three-hour extended meeting held in this West Bank
city, Albright said she and Arafat focused today's discussions on
the issue of fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Telling a press conference, she stressed the importance of
resuming Israeli-Palestinian security cooperation and demanded
the Palestinian Authority (PNA) to take "unilateral actions" to
fight terrorism effectively.
</P>
<P>
She said Arafat reiterated his pledge to U.S. President Bill
Clinton on honoring the commitments to fighting terrorism and also
outlined some steps taken by the PNA to crack down on Islamic
militants.
</P>
<P>
"The truth is that terror threatens peace, terror threatens
the Palestinian Authority, and terror threatens the Palestinian
people. Pursuing peace as partners also means fighting terror as
partners," she said.
</P>
<P>
She requested that the PNA must launch a "comprehensive,
relentless and sustained" fight against terrorism so to save the
peace process, whose continuation is in the interests of both
sides.
</P>
<P>
To balance her demands on the PNA to fight terror, Albright
also expressed understanding to the frustration and anger caused
by Israeli sanctions imposed since the recent suicide bombings in
Jerusalem. She indirectly criticized Israel for taking some steps
to preempt the issues that are reserved for the negotiations in
the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
She urged the Palestinian people not to abandon their hopes
for the peace process, from which she said they would gain
benefit.
</P>
<P>
"I urged the Palestinian people not to lose the hope, not to
give the logics of the Oslo (peace accords), not to abandon the
principles of peace," Albright said, promising that the U.S. would
do its utmost to help solve the current crisis in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same conference, Arafat attacked the Israeli
hardline policies and the sanctions against the Palestinian side,
including the closure, settlement activities, land confiscation,
withholding funds and refusing to release Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader pledged that the PNA is committed to
and would honor the obligations to the Oslo agreements signed
under the U.S. auspices four years ago, saying he would "continue
confronting enemies of peace on both sides." But he called on
Israel to lift all the sanctions and unilateral steps in order to
put an end to violence and achieve a just and comprehensive peace.
</P>
<P>
Albright said Arafat handed her a list of demands on the
Israeli side not to take unilateral steps so to rescue the peace
process, saying she would study it.
</P>
<P>
She made it clear that the U.S. would continue working to
ahcieve peace between Israelis and Palestinians based on the
United Nations resolutions 242 and 338, and the principle of
"land for peace."
</P>
<P>
Highlighting the huge gap between Israel and the PNA, Albright
acknowledged that there was still "a long way to go" to rebuild
the mutual respect and confidence between the two sides, only with
which the peace process can proceed forward.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who arrived here Wednesday for her first Middle East
trip since taking office, has already held talks with Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and other senior Israeli
officials on the current crisis. The Israeli side has conditioned
the continuation of peace process on the PNA's efforts to launch a
war against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Summarizing her talks in the first two days of the three-day
visit, Albright conceded that little progress had been made so
far. "We have not yet been able to see what is the best method to
get the peace process back on track ... I think I still have a
great deal of more work to do," she said.
</P>
<P>
Albright would hold the second round of talks with Netanyahu
later today and with Arafat in Ramallah Friday before heading to
Syria, the second leg of her current Middle East tour.
</P>
<P>
Albright's visit here is aimed at reviving the deeply-troubled
Israeli-Palestinian peace process which has been deadlocked since
March when Israel began building the Har Homa settlement in East
Jerusalem. And the tensions between the sides were worsened by
the recent two suicide bombing attacks by Islamic militants in
central Jerusalem that killed 25 people and wounded over 350
others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
