<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE, U.S. Companies Sign Satellite Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A company of United Arab
Emirates (UAE) and a U.S. company signed a 1-billion-U.S. dollar
contract here today, under which the U.S. company will take on the
construction and operation of the Middle East first satellite
project.
</P>
<P>
The deal, the biggest ever of the kind in the Middle East
region, was inked this afternoon by Mohammad Hassan Omran,
chairman of the UAE's Thuraya Satellite Telecommunications
Company, and Michael J. Houterman, president of U.S. Hughes Space
and Communications International, Inc..
</P>
<P>
The satellite project, namely Thuraya, including two
satellites, is the fifth of the type for mobile telephones in the
world. The service of the satellite will include voice, data, fax
and messaging.
</P>
<P>
The first satellite will be put into orbit in the year 2000 and
it will have a coverage area encompassing nearly 1.8 million
people in the Middle East, North Africa, Eastern Europe including
Turkey, Central Asia and the Indian subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
The bid for the satellite contract was opened nearly two years
ago. Hughes was chosen as the final successful bidder after
beating its three other competitors known as Alcatel, Aerospatial
of France and Lockheed Telecommunications company of the U.S..
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
