<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian FM Terms German FM's statements Amazing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi today termed recent statements by German Foreign
Minister Klaus Kinkel amazing, according to the official news
agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the German Parliament Wednesday, Kinkel was
reported to have termed the trial of liberal Iranian editor
Faraj Sarkuhi as an obstacle to the return of the European
ambassadors and to Tehran-Bonn relations.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that it is very surprising for the German
foreign minister who well knows the international regulations to
make such statements "because the trial of a citizen in a
country is an affair within the jurisdiction of that country."
</P>
<P>
"The trial of Faraj Sarkuhi is not an exception to this
rule," Kharrazi said, adding "even I as the foreign minister of
the Islamic Republic cannot interfere in the affair (Sarkuhi's
trial) let alone the German foreign minister who is a
foreigner."
</P>
<P>
He said that Sarkuhi is being tried fairly and the trial
procedure is being closely watched by the judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Iran has protested against German intervention in the arrest
of the chief editor of Iranian Persian weekly Adineh, who seeks
political asylum in Sweden and Germany.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian editor was arrested along with his brother and
two other smugglers while attempting to make an illegal exit in
Bushehr, a port city in southern Iran, in February.
</P>
<P>
With the exception of Greece, all the EU countries recalled
their ambassadors home from Tehran after the Berlin court last
April implicated top Iranian leaders in the killing of three
Kurdish dissidents and their translator in Berlin in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
