<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Universities Urged to Cooperate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean geologist today
challenged universities in the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) member countries to work together and coordinate
their teaching in the face of declining higher education budgets.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of Geological Society of Zimbabwe Paul Dirks said
declining budgets in SADC colleges and universities were the
major problem constraining the training of geologists, hence the
need for the universities to source their own funding.
</P>
<P>
He said most universities were being forced to cut their
spending without compromising their set standards and
qualifications, a task which he said was very difficult but
required concerted efforts from the various administrations.
</P>
<P>
''We have to organize ourselves to make sure that we
coordinate our teaching so that it becomes relevant to our
environment and all this has to be done despite this major
financial problem that our universities are suffering from,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
Dirks, a lecturer at the University of Zimbabwe's Geology
Department which is co-hosting a 15-day conference on geological
evolution in southern Africa, said universities should also have
links with local industries to ensure their teaching was in line
with market requirements.
</P>
<P>
''Another problem that faces the region and Africa as a whole
is that textbooks that we use are from Europe, and this is a
major constraint as they teach about Europe and not African
geology,'' said Dirks, who urged African governments to provide
budgets for new geology books to be written in Africa.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 delegates from all over the world are attending
the conference which is focusing on the importance of intra-plate
magnetic processes during the evolution of the southern African
crater from the early Archean to recent times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
