<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe, Botswana Improve Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe and Botswana have
taken bold steps to raise the level of economic ties between the
two southern African neighbors.
</P>
<P>
A statement released here today said the two countries'
ministers responsible for industry and commerce met here
Wednesday to consult on issues relating to a 1995 trade agreement
which seeks to bolster the movement of goods and services between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
At the consultative meeting, Zimbabwe's Industry and Commerce
Minister Nathan Shamuyarira and his Botswana counterpart George
Kgoroba acknowledged the improved relations and increased volume
of trade between the two countries, noting, however, that a lot
still needed to be done.
</P>
<P>
''The ministers agreed to amend the trade agreement
expeditiously to accommodate these and any other changes that may
arise to facilitate trade between the two countries,'' said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
They resolved to meet regularly to consult on matters
affecting trade between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Agreement was also reached on the need to include the
cumulative principle in the trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
The principle allows for the inclusion of raw materials
originating from either country in the calculation of the local
content of the products of the exporting country, a move likely
to encourage the use of raw materials from either country.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries has been growing steadily over
the past few years as both countries adopted aggressive
investment promotion initiatives.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe exported 739 million Zimbabwe Dollars worth of goods
last year and imported goods amounting to more than 526 million
during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Currently one U.S. Dollar equals to 11.5 Zimbabwe Dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
