<HEADLINE> BOT Research Center Set Up in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A center specializing in
research on the "build, operate and transfer" (BOT) principle,
which has become an internationally-popular method of collecting
and circulating funds, was established here today.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Australian BOT Research Center, jointly set up by the
East China Political Science and Law Institution and Australia's
Blake Dawson Waldron, International Lawyers, will train government
officials, economic advisors, lawyers and business people in
addition to providing consultative services to the Chinese
government.
</P>
<P>
It will promote the development of BOT projects in China and
advance the use of overseas funds in the country's infrastructural
construction, according to experts here.
</P>
<P>
Blake Dawson Waldron, International Lawyers, with more than
1,000 employees, has worked on many large-scale BOT projects and
is one of the world's largest law firms.  
