<HEADLINE> Mubarak Urges to Protect Third World Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak said here today the interests of the developing countries
should be well protected and double standards be abolished in
pursuit of a new world order.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the inauguration of the 98th Inter-Parliamentary
Union (IPU) Conference, Mubarak said the new world order has to be
just and stable, and to maintain its credibility, double standards
should be shoved aside and the same principles be applied to all
nations.
</P>
<P>
"To find a new world order in the true sense, the North has to
set forth a comprehensive program that would help the Third World
countries surge and grow, in addition to offering technical and
in-kind assistance to these countries," Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
The president blamed industrialized nations of the North for
the damage to the environment, saying that the Third World nations
contribute, but marginally, to the damage.
</P>
<P>
"It is thus unfair to have those nations just taking first
steps on the road to development bear the high costs for the
conservation of the environment," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said there is no choice but to seek together to achieve
conformity among both parts of the world to set up a new system of
international relations, which are based on just and comprehensive
peace, balanced and sustained development and real democracy.
</P>
<P>
"The peace we speak of is peace for all the people in the
world, with no differentiation between countries being rich or
poor, large or small, advanced or on the road to progress," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He said it is appropriate that parliamentarians at the
conference discuss such "urgent" issues of labor and
globalization, but he stressed that the interests of the Third
World have to be taken into account when drafting international
economic relations in the future.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,600 parliamentarians from 138 member states
together with representatives of 20 international organizations
are taking part in the biannual conference on September 11-16.
</P>
<P>
The 138-member IPU was formed in 1889 to promote democratic
representation through personal contact of MPs and promote
international peace and cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
