<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: China Gives Top Priority to Coal-Mining Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Coal Industry
today announced that all coal mines are required to install
underground gas-fueled warning lamps in the coming three to five
years.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister Wang Xianzheng made the announcement today in a
national tele-conference on safety in coal-mining. He also said
that miners have the rights to refuse working under unsafe
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts see this as a major step taken by the Chinese
government to step up mining safety and eliminate hidden troubles,
so as to ultimately ensure the safety of the miners.
</P>
<P>
According to sources at the ministry, the government has
attached great importance to safe production in coal mines. Huge
amounts of funding have been invested in the development of
related technology and equipment.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, a series of substantial measures have been
adopted to administrate coal mines according to law in reinforcing
safe mining. Moreover, the ministry carries out nationwide
regulation checks.
</P>
<P>
This year, the ministry has made gas-control a key task for the
safety campaign. Coal mines with poor air circulation have been
forced to reduce their output and to improve and renovate the
ventilation systems.
</P>
<P>
Many mines have invested heavily in installing and upgrading
their gas-run equipment.
</P>
<P>
To reinforce safety supervision, the ministry has asked local
coal-mining administrations to allow supervisors to oversee the
work on behalf of the administration.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, nationwide training courses have been held this
year to improve the miners' technical quality and their knowledge
on safety and law.
</P>
<P>
And the efforts have paid off.
</P>
<P>
In the first eight months of this year, the ratio of casualties
to occur during the production of every one million tons of coal
by coal mines directly under the ministry had plunged by 53.8
percent, compared with the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The emphasis on safe mining has boosted China's coal production
remarkably. Official statistics show that the country turned out
1.35 billion tons of raw coal in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Denies Nuclear Deal With Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Atomic
Energy Corporation (AEC) has never been involved in business
transactions with Iran, nor is any being considered at present,
Minister of Mineral and Energy Affairs Penuell Maduma said today.
</P>
<P>
In a written reply to parliament, the minister said AEC chief
Woldo Stumpf never held a meeting with Iranian Deputy Minister of
Atomic Affairs Reza Amrollahi, as claimed by local and foreign
media.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Stumpf had confirmed that the only meeting he, or any
other AEC officials had ever had with any Iranian government
officials, had taken place in March 1995 in a public restaurant
in Cape Town, with Iranian Petroleum Minister Gholamreza
Aghazadeh, said Maduna.
</P>
<P>
Stumpf had been asked to attend the courtesy dinner by former
Mineral and Energy Affairs Minister Pik Botha during Aghazadeh's
visit to South Africa in connection with a possible oil storage
deal at Saldanha military base in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Some "general matters of interest in the nuclear area" had
been discussed at he dinner, Maduna admitted.
</P>
<P>
These included South Africa's termination of its nuclear
weapons program and its accession to the United Nations
non-proliferation treaty, the uncompleted German busher power
reactor in Iran, and South Africa's policy toward uranium
exports.
</P>
<P>
Stumpf therefore denied press reports that he had received
instructions by President Nelson Mandela's office to meet
secretly in Cape Town with Amrollahi in connection with an
Iranian bid to purchase items for manufacturing nuclear weapons,
Maduna said.
</P>
<P>
"No further contact had been undertaken since then," Maduna
stressed, adding or even before then, with any Iranian government
officials and that the AEC had had no business or other dealings
with Iran in the past, nor were any being considered at present.
</P>
<P>
Local and foreign media reported recently that South Africa
has reached some kind of agreement with Iran to help the country
upgrade its nuclear capacity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues Regulations on Nuclear Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng
signed a decree on Wednesday to issue and implement the
regulations on control of nuclear exports from China.
</P>
<P>
The regulations were adopted at the 61st regular meeting of the
State Council on August 1.
</P>
<P>
According to the new regulations, China exercises control over
nuclear exports and strictly carries out its international
obligations on non-proliferation of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
All nuclear exports should abide by the relevant state laws and
administrative rules, and must not harm the state security and
public interest.
</P>
<P>
Foreign governments, which are the recipients of nuclear
exports, are to pledge that they will not use for other purposes
the Chinese-supplied nuclear materials and nuclear equipment or
non-nuclear materials used for reactors.
</P>
<P>
The foreign governments must sign a supervision agreement with
the International Atomic Energy Agency and must accept the body's
supervision over Chinese nuclear supplies, it stresses.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the recipients must pledge that they will not
transfer the Chinese nuclear supplies to any third party, and
those involved in a third party-transfer agreed to by the Chinese
suppliers bear the responsibilities set for those who have
directly imported from China, according to the regulations.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear exports are conducted by the monopoly exporters
authorized by the State Council, and other institutions and
individuals are not allowed to export, the decree said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Army Fires at Ecomog Jet Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Sierra Leonean armed
forces today fired at the jet fighter of the west African
peacekeeping force known as Ecomog in Freetown to enforce
economic embargo.
</P>
<P>
Military junta spokesman Aliu Koroma said a Nigeria plane
belonging to Ecomog attacked the port twice today and dropped a
bomb but only to miss the target.
</P>
<P>
No one has been hurt, he confirmed in an interview with the
British Broadcasting Corporation monitored here.
</P>
<P>
"We are firing at them heavily for them to know that we are
alert. We are not going to take chance at all," the spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
"As a responsible government, we have to establish ourselves,
let these people understand that this is our territorial
integrity. We are a sovereign state," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the Ecomog plane flying over the
port regularly is "to intimate our people, to provoke us, making
life uneasy for our people".
</P>
<P>
"It is very much acceptable," he added.
</P>
<P>
This is not the first time the junta accused the Ecomog plane
of bombing the port in Freetown since Ecomog announced last
Friday that it would attack any violators of the embargo.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, the junta claimed that some 20 civilians were
killed in an Ecomog air raid.
</P>
<P>
But Ecomog force commander Major-General Victor Malu rejected
the accusation, saying that Ecomog was attacking a vessel trying
to unloading arms and ammunition, among other goods, and no
civilian was killed in the exercise.
</P>
<P>
A contingent of the Sierra Leone army equipped with
anti-aircraft guns was stationed at the port to ward off air
attack on ships there.
</P>
<P>
The embargo was approved by west African leaders at a summit
last month to force the junta, which seized power in a coup in
May, to step down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
