<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Negotiating Shipping Treaties With 37 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is
negotiating merchant shipping agreements with 37 countries, the
Foreign Affairs Ministry said in a statement today.
</P>
<P>
Four such accords had already been signed, while two more were
at an advanced stage, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The agreements allow for vessels from the countries concerned
to sail freely between each other's ports. They also provide for
the setting up of bilateral committees to promote merchant
shipping between the countries.
</P>
<P>
Treaties had been concluded with Madagascar, the Netherlands,
Mozambique and Malaysia. Accords with Algeria and Egypt were
yesterday initialed by officials of the respective countries,
and would be soon formalized by the governments concerned, the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Other countries showing an interest in similar agreement with
South Africa included Germany, Bulgaria, Poland, France, Cuba,
the United Kingdom, Kenya, Mexico and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Formalized cooperation in merchant shipping between South
Africa and other seafaring nations had until recently been
virtually non-existent, the ministry said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
