<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Parliament Pays Tribute to Black </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's
parliament today agreed to a motion paying tribute to Steve Biko,
the black consciousness leader who died from cruel torture by
white police on September 12, 1977.
</P>
<P>
The motion, moved by ruling African National Congress on the
20th anniversary of Biko's death, said parliament recognized
Biko's contribution to the struggle for freedom and the fight
against apartheid.
</P>
<P>
Pan Africanist Congress leader Stanley Magoba said Biko's
death had been a shame to South Africa -- not only the way he had
died, but the extent to which he had been harassed.
</P>
<P>
Jacko Maree, National Party member, said his party
"emotionally shared" the feelings of others at the anniversary of
Biko's death, and agreed that the black activist's death had been
an event which should never have occurred.
</P>
<P>
Nhlahla Zulu, member of Inkatha Freedom Party, called on all
those responsible for Biko's death to apologize to the whole
South African nation, and not just to his relatives and members
of the black consciousness movement.
</P>
<P>
Douglas Gibson, Democratic Party member, said the anniversary
was an opportunity for parliament to dedicate itself to ensuring
that human rights were never again trampled on in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's National Association of Democratic Lawyers
today also issued a statement in memory of Biko.
</P>
<P>
The association said it regarded September 12 as a special day
of remembrance of Biko's life and contribution to the liberation
of South Africa from the yoke of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
"As a non-sexist, non-racialist, sofetly-spoken human being,
Steve would not have objected to being called the 'mother' of
black consciousness in South Africa," the statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
