<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profits Soar for French Automaker in 1st Half of 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The French automaker Renault
gained 1.672 billion francs (280 million U.S. dollars) of profits
in the first half of 1997, compared with 158 million francs (31.6
million U.S. dollars) in the first half of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The soaring of profits partly resulted from the transfer of 419
million francs (69 million U.S. dollars) of stocks of the
Elf-Aquitaine oil group previously held by Renault, said Agence
France-Presse (AFP) quoting Renault sources.
</P>
<P>
The improvement of the results from the automobile making
branch of the group also contributed to the increase of profits.
</P>
<P>
The auto making branch of Renault reported a loss of 162
million francs (27 million U.S. dollars) in the first half of this
year, compared with 911 million francs (182 million U.S. dollars)
in the first half of last year, reported AFP.
</P>
<P>
The president of Renault, Louis Schweitzer, is carrying out a
fundamental restructuring of the auto group which is half private
and half public in terms of its stock holders.
</P>
<P>
Renault's decision in February to close its assembly plant in
Vilvoorde, Belgium, had aroused strong protests from unions and
the Belgian government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
