<HEADLINE> Boeing's Stretched Version Aimed at Asian Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Boeing's stretched
version of 777, whose first flight is scheduled for next month, is
aimed at high-density routes such as those in the Far East.
</P>
<P>
A product to compete with Airbus for the Asian market, the
first Boeing 777-300 airliner was rolled out at Boeing's plant in
Seattle earlier this week. Its first delivery to Cathay Pacific of
Hong Kong is scheduled for May 1988.
</P>
<P>
Capable of carrying some 20 percent more passengers, the new
model has been designed for regions, where crowed airports do not
have room for more planes, according to Larry Dickenson, Boeing
vice-president for international sales in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
He predicted the stretched 777 would become the "flagship
airplane for most of the Asia airplane fleets." Most of the 52
orders for the new model came for Asian airlines.
</P>
<P>
At 73.8 meters, the new aircraft is three meters long than
Boeing jumbo 747-400. The stretched fuselage allows "a typical
three-class" configuration to increase from 328 to 384 passengers.
In a two-class configuration it can carry up to 479 people, while
in an all-economy layout the capacity could reach 550 passengers.
</P>
<P>
Its larger fuel tanks enable the aircraft to keep its nonstop
range at 10,370 k. A typical route would be Tokyo to Singapore,
Honolulu to Seoul or San Francisco to Tokyo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
