<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: Security, Oslo Process Important to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madelein Albright today demanded both Israel and the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) to further cooperate on security and
honor Oslo peace process.
</P>
<P>
Albright was addressing the students and teachers of the High
School of Arts and Sciences of Jerusalem on the U.S. basic
principles for moving the negotiation process forward.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. believes that security cooperation between Israel and
the PNA is vital for moving the peace process forward, and both
sides should take concrete steps in this direction, she said.
</P>
<P>
Security cooperation requires the leadership of both Israel and
the PNA, particularly the PNA side, to show red lights to
terrorism, she said.
</P>
<P>
The second basic principle is that the Oslo process must be
honored by both sides, she said.
</P>
<P>
In this aspect, both Israel and the PNA must renew and
reinforce their commitments and responsibilities to the Oslo
accords reached four years ago and there can be no back-off from
the Oslo commitment, she said.
</P>
<P>
This means that Israel should refrain from unilateral acts,
including the implementation of the provocative policies of
expansion of settlements, home demolition, withholding of taxes
and the confiscation of IDs of the Palestinians because such acts
might undermine the confidence of the Palestinians, she said.
</P>
<P>
The United States believes that the halt of such unilateral
acts by Israel could create an atmosphere which will be conducive
to the acceleration of achieving a final peace agreement, she
added.
</P>
<P>
Israel should do all it can to avoid harming the Palestinian
economy and the welfare of its people, she said.
</P>
<P>
Finally, she said, both Israel and the PNA must understand the
real meaning of peace and strengthen the partnership between the
two sides so that the final peace can be realized, she said.
</P>
<P>
Albright arrived here Wednesday for a three-day visit in a
bid to help restore the Middle East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
