<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Russia's Statement on Missiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government today
welcomed a Russian statement that the S-300 anti-aircraft
missile system will not be deployed in Cyprus once the Turkish
troops are withdrawn from the island, a government spokesman said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, government spokesman
Manolis Christofides described a statement Wednesday by the
Russian president's spokesman, Serguel Yastrjembsky, as "a right
approach and in line with the substance of the Cyprus question."
</P>
<P>
The Russian official's statement, Christofides said,
"introduces the correct approach toward promoting a Cyprus
solution."
</P>
<P>
Yastrjembsky said Wednesday that "only if Turkish troops were
withdrawn from Cyprus there would be no delivery of the S-300 to
Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
The Russian spokesman also defended the legitimate right of
the government of Cyprus to purchase and deploy the S-300
missiles, which he described as pure defensive character.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian ambassador to Cyprus Georgi Muratov told
reporters here today that the missiles would be in Cyprus in a
year's time, noting that the only development that could prevent
their deployment would be the demilitarization of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He said Turkish threats that the surface-to-air missiles
should not be deployed on the island run contrary to every rule
of international law.
</P>
<P>
The Russian ambassador said that the contract signed early
this year between the Cypriot government and the Russian
manufacturers of the S-300 system would be fully honored.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Turkey's search of merchant ships passing
through the Bosporus Straits, in an effort to prevent the
deployment of the missiles in Cyprus, Muratov stressed that
those tactics should be terminated as they violate free
navigation.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia was protesting against the Turkish acts and
called on other countries affected to protest as well.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' decision to purchase the Russian-made S-300 missile
system early this year has triggered Turkey's threats that it
will launch pre-emptive strike against Cyprus if they are
deployed.
</P>
<P>
But the Cypriot government has repeatedly said that the deal
could be canceled if Turkey and Turkish Cypriots agree to
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides' proposal for demilitarization
of the island, or if there is substantial progress on the Cyprus
problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
