<HEADLINE> Jordan: Albright's Mideast Visit Could Be Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Jordan today reiterated its
reserved optimism about United States' Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's maiden trip to the Middle East after taking
office.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of State for Information Affair Samir
Mutawe said that the Middle East peace process might see a better
turn if there is a good coordination between the Arab states and
Albright.
</P>
<P>
Albright's mission would succeed in salvaging the stalled peace
process if she can help curb the Jewish settlements in Arab land
and bring about the implementation of the signed agreements
between the Israelis and Palestinians, Radio Jordan quoted Mutawe
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mutawe said that Israeli withdrawal from all the
occupied Arab land and its commitments to the peace agreements
would guarantee a comprehensive and just peace.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the coordination between the United
States represented by Albright's current trip and those of the
Arab states could release the peace process from the present
deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who arrived in Israel Wednesday, has stressed that
the Palestinians should act in response to the Israeli demands and
make more efforts to combat terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
In Jerusalem today, she also asked the Israeli side to stop
building Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem, an issuing leading
the peace process to a crisis since March.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian minister of state made these remarks amid
Palestinian complaints about Albright's trip. Palestinian Minister
of Higher Education Hanan Ashrawi Wednesday criticized that
Albright began her visit in "one-sided approach."
</P>
<P>
Albright will later visit Jordan, Egypt, Syria, Saudi Arabia
and possibly Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has been playing a major role in the peace process
and its Middle East special Envoy Dennis Ross had made several
rounds of shuttle diplomacy between Washington and the region in
preparation for Albright's visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
