<HEADLINE> UAE-based Satellite Company Seeks Bank Loans for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Thuraya Satellite
Telecommunications Company is seeking bank loans for a satellite
project costing 1 billion U.S. dollars, chairman of the company
Mohammad Hassan Omran said here today.
</P>
<P>
"For constructing and operating the project, we will cost
nearly 1 billion dollars in 12 to 15 years," said Omran at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
"We now have a capital of some 500 million dollars. The others
will be collected through bank loans," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Thuraya company, based in the Arab United Emirates (UAE),
is planning to set up a mobile telephone satellite system. It
signed this afternoon a contract with the U.S. Hughes Space and
Communications International, Inc. which will carry out the
construction and operation of the project.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. company president, Michael Houterman, said today that it
is now seeking subcontractors for manufacturing launching
services, ground facilities and 250,000 hand-held telephones.
</P>
<P>
The satellite project is the biggest ever of its kind in the
Middle East. With the services of voice, data, fax and messaging,
it will cover the areas of the Middle East, North Africa, Eastern
Europe, Central Asia and Indian subcontinent with a population of
nearly 1.8 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
