<HEADLINE> Zambia Makes Apology to British High Commissioner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government here
today officially apologized to the British government and its
diplomatic representative for "reckless remarks" made by a senior
official, reported Zambia News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference held in the capital, finance minister
Ronald Penza said it would be foolish to risk the investment flow
by making "reckless" remarks about Patrick Nixon, British high
commissioner to Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Penza told reporters that he has made an apology to Nixon on
behalf of the Zambian government, while describing him as a
"tremendous asset" in rebuilding Zambia's relationship with
Britian.
</P>
<P>
This apology was offered after Zambian foreign minister
Lawrence Shimba accused Wednesday Nixon of sending the British
government false reports about the democratization in Zambia,
which greatly affected aid flow to the country.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with a six-member parliamentary delegation from
Britian, who arrived in Lusaka Tuesday on an 8-day visit to study
Zambia's legal system and review the programmes under British
aid, Shimba charged that Nixon refused to cooperate with the
Zambian government.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to Britian to ignore Nixon's "negative" reports on
grounds that his country is going ahead with its democratization
process which began in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Zambia, a member of the Commonwealth and with an average GDP
of 370 U.S. dollars per capita, receives hundreds of millions of
dollars from the Western donor countries every year. 
</P>
