<HEADLINE> Car Fuel Prices Rise Again in Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A stronger dollar caused car
fuel prices in Belgium to rise once more to a new high since 1985,
local television reported today.
</P>
<P>
The RTBF television said that the price rise was just a month
away from the previous hikes that shot local car fuel prices to as
high as 40.1 Belgian francs (1.02 U.S. dollars) for a liter of
unleaded petroleum.
</P>
<P>
Today's increase added another 0.3 franc to the price tag.
</P>
<P>
Local economists fear that car fuel prices may rise further due
to the rising dollar and the rising price on international
petroleum markets.
</P>
<P>
A liter of unleaded petroleum sold for 28.1 francs per liter in
July 1989 when the exchange rate was at around 38 francs for a
dollar. The dollar fetched 37 francs today.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian franc has been losing ground against the dollar
ever since the Mexican peso crisis in late 1994 and early 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
