<HEADLINE> US Trade Deficit in Current Account Declines in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S trade deficit in
the current account decreased slightly to 39 billion U.S. dollars
in the second quarter of this year as the growth of exports
outpaced the increase in imports.
</P>
<P>
The imbalance in the U.S. current account slipped 2.4 percent
from a first-quarter deficit of 40 billion dollars, the Commerce
Department said in a report released here today.
</P>
<P>
The decrease reflected a 5.5 percent increase in merchandise
exports to 171.5 billion dollars while merchandise imports climbed
up by 2.9 percent to 218.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The current account is the broadest measure of foreign trade,
including not only sales of goods but also services, investment
flows and foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
The improvement in the deficit helped slow down the overall
economic growth in the second quarter. The gross domestic product
grew at a healthy 3.6 percent pace following a strong advance at a
4.9 percent rate in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
As usual, this country had a surplus in services. It was 20.5
billion dollars in the second quarter, the same as in the first.
</P>
<P>
Despite the slight improvement in the overall current account,
the deficit during the first half of 1997 was running at an annual
rate of 158 billion dollars, which is higher than the 148.2
billion dollar deficit in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
