<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Moves to Harmonize Economic Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) has urged its member countries to set up
a national economic policy implementation committee to ensure
that they comply with its economic integration program through
harmonized policies.
</P>
<P>
This was indicated in a document drawn up by the ECOWAS
Secretariat, "harmonization of economic and financial policies of
ECOWAS", the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The committee is necessary to align national economic policies
with the regional macro-economic convergence objective for the
benefit of the integration process, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, the committee would comprise
members from government ministries, banking and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS's major convergence objectives include a budget
deficit/GDP (Gross Domestic Product) ratio of five percent by
1998 year and a maximum of three percent subsequently for member
states.
</P>
<P>
Others include unification of exchange rates and the removal
of over-valuation by 1998, removal of payment restrictions on
current account transactions between 1998 to the year 2,000.
</P>
<P>
Member countries are also expected to progressively reduce
their borrowing from their central banks to a ceiling of 10
percent of fiscal revenue by 1998.
</P>
<P>
The document noted, however, most member countries could not
sustain the success attained in the program because of structural
weakness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, GCC Discuss Ways to Improve Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Ambassador to
Saudi Arabia Ridha Nouri met today with the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) Secretary General Jamil Al-Hujailan to discuss ways
of improving and strengthening relations between Iran and GCC
countries, Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the GCC said Nouri and Hujailan also
exchanged views on the latest developments of the Middle East and
international situations. But no details were given in the report.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is as a part of the latest drive by Iran and the
GCC countries to improve their long-strained relations, especially
after Mohammad Khatami, a moderate cleric, was sworn in as Iran's
new president in August.
</P>
<P>
Khatami made a declaration on Wednesday that "peace and
stability in the region is tied on the level of cooperation
between Iran and the Gulf Arab states," expressing a willingness
to strengthen ties with GCC countries and establish solid eternal
peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hujailan said recently that the GCC, grouping Saudi
Arabia, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman and
Qatar, welcomes any Iranian initiative and that "one of the
contents of the GCC policy is to establish a strong relation with
a large neighboring country like Iran."
</P>
<P>
Omani Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Yousef Bin Alawi
Bin Abdullah visited Iran Tuesday and Qatari Foreign Minister
Sheikh Hamad bin Jassem bin Jaber Al-Thani is also expected to
visit Tehran Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, observers do not expect major changes in the GCC-Iran
relations in the near future, with many issues, particularly the
dispute over the sovereignty of three gulf islands between Iran
and the UAE hindering in the way.
</P>
<P>
The islands of Abu Mousa, Greater and Lesser Tunb are occupied
by Iran, but also claimed by the UAE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
