<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insecurity Growing in Eastern Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The security situation is
worsening in the east part of the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC) with sporadic exchanges of gunfire heard at night in the
towns of Goma and Bukavu.
</P>
<P>
A release issued by the U.N. Integrated Regional Information
Network quoted an aid worker as saying that Bunyakiri, about 80
kilometers north of Bukavu, was occupied by rebels at the end of
last week.
</P>
<P>
The release reaching here today noted that some anti-Tutsi
groups were forming loose alliances directed at the
Tutsi-dominated forces of President Laurent Kabila and his
Rwandan allies.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said that a new rebel group Democratic
Resistance Alliance (DRA) was set up last month with the stated
aim of "liberating" eastern DRC.
</P>
<P>
One of the DRA leaders is Celestin Bembe who held the post of
"First Vice-President" in Mobutu's last government and is
allegedly well-known for his anti-Tutsi sentiments.
</P>
<P>
The rebel group reportedly based in Tanzania groups opposition
forces from the DRC, Burundi, Rwanda and Uganda, according to a
DRC newspaper "La Reference Plus" report.
</P>
<P>
Some rebel groups based in Fizi and Masisi regions are made of
local people who are resentful at the dominance of the Bayarwanda
Tutsis within Kabila's army.
</P>
<P>
The release said that President Kabila warned on Monday that
he would not tolerate the reorganization of anti-government
forces and would quickly take action to crush them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
