<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northern Ireland's Economy in Strong Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELFAST, Northern Ireland, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Northern
Ireland's economy is healthier than it has been for decades and
will continue to develop until the end of the century, a local
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Its industrial production increased by over 13 percent during
the past five years compared with 5.9 percent for the UK as a
whole and 3.6 percent for the EU economies in aggregate.
</P>
<P>
The number of people in employment in Northern Ireland --
currently running at record levels -- has grown by 6.9 percent
over the last five years compared with 1.7 percent in the whole
country.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment has fallen steadily from a peak of 17.2 percent in
October 1986 to a 17-year low of 7.9 percent in July 1997.
Overall, unemployment has fallen by some 30 percent since July
1996.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a gathering here with London-based foreign
correspondents, John McGuckian, chairman of the Industrial
Development Board for Northern Ireland, said, "All of these
developments have contributed to the very real feeling of hope,
optimism and determination which the people of Northern Ireland
have about their future."
</P>
<P>
With the resumption of talks on a political settlement for
Northern Ireland which Sinn Fein will take part in for the first
time, the chairman said, "It will have very positive impacts on
Northern Ireland's economy."
</P>
<P>
The Northern Ireland Economic Research Center expects this
favorable performance to continue through into the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Its GDP is expected to increase by 3-4 percent per annum until
the end of the century -- a level of around 1.5 percent per annum
faster than that forecast for the UK as a whole. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
