<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-11 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: Too Early to Judge Arafat's Pledge to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Commenting on Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat's pledge to fight terrorism, Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said today that it was too early to
judge Arafat's real actions.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks at a news conference after the
second round of talks with visiting United States Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, who is here on a rescue mission to
save the deeply-troubled Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite Arafat's promise, it was still too early
to judge whether there would be any real movements on the
Palestinian side to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Albright went directly into the meeting with Netanyahu late
in the afternoon at the Prime Minister's office right after
returning from Ramallah, West Bank, where she held a marathon
meeting with Arafat to discuss ways to break the deadlock in
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
While Arafat reiterated to Albright his promise to fight
Islamic militants, he also demanded Israel stop violating its
commitments to the signed peace accords by lifting the closure on
Palestinian-held areas, releasing the frozen funds and stopping
settlement activities.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same conference, Albright said she discussed
with Netanyahu the issue of Israel's withholding of about 30
million U.S. dollars remaining tax revenues owed to the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA), saying that she regarded it
as an inappropriate measure unrelated to the security issue.
</P>
<P>
She also stressed to Netanyahu the principle of reciprocity
on avoiding taking unilateral steps to preempt the final-status
talks. It remained unclear whether she proposed a halt to
Israeli settlement activities which have become the major
obstacle in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In earlier remarks, Albright has urged Israel to create a
favorable environment to rebuild mutual trust and confidence
with the PNA in order to get the peace process back on track.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu confirmed that he and Albright talked about a wide
range of reciprocity issues, including Israeli obligations which
he promised to fulfill if the PNA acts to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that Albright's visit would bring about
"concrete and tangible changes" to the current crisis. But he
warned that Israel is still in "a state of danger" because of
concrete intelligence warnings about more terror attacks.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the issues on resuming the Israeli-Palestinian
peace process, the two leaders also discussed the threats of
Iran's nuclear weapon program and long-range missile development
and the possibility of reviving the suspended talks between
Israel and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Albright and Netanyahu are to hold private dinner meeting
tonight to continue discussions. On Friday, Albright is expected
to return to Ramallah to hold the second round of talks with
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
She will leave for Damascus to visit Syria late Friday, at
the second leg of her first Middle East tour that will also take
her to Egypt, Jordan and Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
