<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most of Kenyan MPs Agree on IPPG Reform Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A majority of Kenyan
lawmakers agreed on a package of political reforms submitted by
the Inter-Party Parliamental Group (IPPG) at the third plenary
session starting today, IPPG Secretary George Anyona told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The IPPG suggested that the Electoral Commission be more
broad-based, transparency in the casting of votes be ensured, the
winning president be permitted to form a coalition government,
and the election timetable be prepared in consultation with all
parties involved.
</P>
<P>
A total of 132 parliamentary members, more than 40 of them
from the opposition, attended the session and reached a consensus
on the package, said Anyona, adding the figure meets the
two-third majority demand for the 200-seat house to enact any
bill.
</P>
<P>
President Daniel arap Moi, 74 and in power for 19 years,
expressed his support to the IPPG package when meeting with the
IPPG Coordinating Committee today.
</P>
<P>
The group, formed by the ruling Kenya African National Union
(KANU) and the Opposition, also proposed to have 12 laws repealed
or amended partly in a bid to ensure freedom of expression and
equitable access of all political parties to public media.
</P>
<P>
Political prisoners should be released, all political parties
be permitted to register, and the law allowing detention without
trial be repealed, the IPPG recommended.
</P>
<P>
However, opposition lawmakers appeared to have given up during
the coming general elections one of their key demands that the
future president should obtain a 50 percent majority of the total
votes in addition to the 25 percent votes in five of the eight
provinces.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the opposition umbrella body, the National Convention
Executive Council (NCEC), dismissed the IPPG's work and planned
to call national strikes and protests on September 17-18 and
October 8-9 to press for total constitutional reforms before the
elections.
</P>
<P>
The NCEC, which fails to register, also organized a rally on
Sunday in Kisumu, the third-largest city of Kenya. But the rally
flopped after nine opposition leaders were detained at Kisumu
airport.
</P>
<P>
As many as 17 foreign embassies, mainly from western
countries, announced Saturday they back the current parliamentary
inter-party talks. The diplomatic community here were also
invited to attend the parliament's third plenary session as
observers.
</P>
<P>
KANU, which has firmly rejected talks with the NCEC, will open
its National Delegate Conference on September 16 over reform
talks and the election. At such a conference before the first
multi-party election in 1992, Moi was elected as KANU's sole
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
Moi has recently claimed that he would announce the poll date
soon.
</P>
<P>
Political atmosphere has been tightening in the country
following several rounds of violent clashes between the
government and the opposition since May, the key loan cut by the
International Monetary Fund and continuous killings on the Coast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
