<HEADLINE> Four-Party Peace Talks to Be Held Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The second four-party
peace talks on the Korean Peninsula will be held late next week
after Senior officials from the United States and the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) made an agreement in their
two-day Beijing consultations, the State Department announced
today.
</P>
<P>
Next week's preparatory meeting, scheduled for September 18-19
in New York, "is to decide arrangements for the four-party plenary
session," spokesman James Foley said at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the DPRK, South Korea, the United States and
China will attend the preparatory meeting at Columbia University's
School of International and Public Affairs, Foley added.
</P>
<P>
Foley declined to say whether the U.S. and DPRK officials had
reached any agreement in their Beijing talks for the DPRK to
participate in next week's meeting. He said he had nothing to
comment "on that issue from the briefing podium."
</P>
<P>
He would neither disclose the discussions between the U.S. and
DPRK officials on the defection of two DPRK diplomats, Chang
Sung-gil and Chang Sung-ho, whom had been granted asylum by the
United States.
</P>
<P>
"There is no linkage between the Chang case and the four-party
peace process or indeed any other issue," Foley told reporters.
"We believe that all sides are participating in the process
because it is in their interests to do so and because it's
important for advancing and ensuring peace across the Korean
Peninsula, whatever bilateral concerns may exist."
</P>
<P>
Foley also said that before the preparatory meeting, there will
be bilateral meetings between the participants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
