<HEADLINE> Tanzanian PM Urges for Saving of Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime
Minister Frederick Sumaye today urged people to exercise prudence
in the use of cereals and legumes to meet the imminent food
shortage in the country.
</P>
<P>
Sumaye told reporters here that Tanzania will face a
900,000-ton shortage in the next nine months, a consignment which
the government will have to import.
</P>
<P>
He said that as a measure to curb the food shortage, the
government has formed special committees from the ward to
district level to monitor the food situation in their respective
areas.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is need for all people to take
precautionary measures against the shortage, including a stop to
making local brews.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also called upon the public to mobilize
resources, including cropping their animals to raise money to buy
food during the hard period.
</P>
<P>
On food smuggling, Sumaye said that stern action should be
taken against the smugglers and the intercepted consignments
should be auctioned.
</P>
<P>
The imminent food shortage resulted from grave drought in the
past year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
