<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- A company of United Arab Emirates (UAE) and a
U.S. company signed a 1-billion-U.S. dollar contract here today,
under which the U.S. company will take on the construction and
operation of the Middle East first satellite project.
</P>
<P>
The deal, the biggest ever of the kind in the Middle East
region, was inked this afternoon by Mohammad Hassan Omran,
chairman of the UAE's Thuraya Satellite Telecommunications
Company, and Michael J. Houterman, president of U.S. Hughes Space
and Communications International, Inc..
</P>
<P>
The satellite project, namely Thuraya, including two
satellites, is the fifth of the type for mobile telephones in the
world. The service of the satellite will include voice, data, fax
and messaging.
</P>
<P>
The first satellite will be put into orbit in the year 2000 and
it will have a coverage area encompassing nearly 1.8 million
people in the Middle East, North Africa, Eastern Europe including
Turkey, Central Asia and the Indian subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
The bid for the satellite contract was opened nearly two years
ago. Hughes was chosen as the final successful bidder after
beating its three other competitors known as Alcatel, Aerospatial
of France and Lockheed Telecommunications company of the U.S..
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A Jordanian delegation led by Industry and Trade
Secretary General Mohammad Halaiqa is in Washington for seeking
help from some U.S. organizations on issues related to Jordan's
entry to the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Newspapers here today quoted Tamam Al Ghoul, head of the WTO
unit at the ministry of industry, Trade and Supply, as saying that
the delegation would enlist the help from the U.S. organizations
in preparing for the negotiations on Jordan's joining the world
trade body.
</P>
<P>
The delegation also aimed to benefit from the experiences of
the organizations in participating such negotiations, she said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the talks would cover the prospect of arranging for
Jordanian personnel to be trained by these organizations on
following up issues pertaining to the upcoming negotiations, she
added.
</P>
<P>
Along with Jordan, other Arab countries like Saudi Arabia,
Algeria, Oman and Sudan are negotiating with the WTO while Syria
and Lebanon are studying the prospect of applying to join the
organization.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon signed Wednesday with the European Investment
Bank (EIB) three financial agreements totalling 164 million
U.S. dollars, a Lebanese Central News Agency report said.
</P>
<P>
The electricity sector, the state of road networks and the
treatment of undrinkable water are the subjects agreed upon, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The deals have made the total loans granted by EIB since 1993
reach 540 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
These loans are mainly used in the construction of Beirut
Airport, Beirut Port, water and electric projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
