<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All Senate Democrats Support McCain-Feingold Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Democratic leaders said
Thursday that all 45 Senate Democrats are ready to vote for the
McCain-Feingold campaign finance reform bill.
</P>
<P>
The bipartisan bill would prohibit parties from collecting
unlimited "soft money" contributions, the donations that can't be
used for direct candidate support and is supposed to pay for
generic election activities. It would also authorize voluntary
spending limits for candidates in exchange for reduced
broadcast-advertising costs.
</P>
<P>
The 45 democrats, in a letter to Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, a Republican of Mississippi, asked that Lott schedule a vote
soon on the legislation. Democrats noted that with three
Republican senators already co-sponsoring the bill, only two
Republican votes are needed to move it through the Senate.
</P>
<P>
"Your willingness to schedule... an up-or-down vote, coupled
with the support of only two additional Republican senators, could
break 10 years of gridlock on this matter," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
Lott still believes that ongoing Senate hearings into
questionable money raising during the 1996 campaign should be
finished before laws that oversee the process are revamped, said
Susan Irby, Lott's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
Senator John McCain, a Republican of Arizona, one of the bill's
sponsors, said his talks with Lott to bring the issue to the floor
this year "have shown progress."
</P>
<P>
However, Irby said Lott has not promised a vote on the issue in
1997. Congressional leaders hope to adjourn for the year in
October or November.
</P>
<P>
The bill's other chief sponsor, Senator Russell Feingold,
Democrat of Wisconsin, joining Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle,
at a news conference to announce the Democratic letter.
</P>
<P>
With the long resistance to overhauling the current
campaign-finance laws from incumbents of both parties, who find
the current system comfortable, the prospects for an early vote
remain questionable.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton has endorsed the bill for months and
earlier this year called for its passage by July 4.
</P>
<P>
In the House in recent weeks, Democrats have been forcing
frequent procedural votes to delay the chamber's work in an effort
to pressure Republican leaders there to schedule a vote on the
legislation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
