<HEADLINE> Mozambique's Police Reform Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 11 (Xinhua) -- A plan to restructure
and retrain Mozambique's police force has not yet begun, with
fingers of blame pointing to bureaucratic procedures of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here today from Maputo quoted government
officials as saying that the Spanish police officers who are
supposed to be in charge of retraining the Mozambicans are
already in the country.
</P>
<P>
But the foreign police officers are angry and demoralized at
the constant delays that prevent them from starting their work.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands and Spain have donated about 17 million U.S.
Dollars to the project.
</P>
<P>
Other donors, such as Italy, have indicated they will join at
a later stage, after clear evidence the performance of the police
is improving.
</P>
<P>
Under agreements signed between the donors and the Mozambican
government, the funds are handled by the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
Four advisors from the Spanish civil guards arrived in
Mozambique in July, expecting to begin their work at once.
</P>
<P>
But they found the UNDP is not releasing the money required to
begin the program properly, the reports said. 
</P>
