<HEADLINE> WWF to Develop Environmental Education in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The World Wide Fund for
Nature (WWF) Cameroun Program Office is planning to reorientate
activities in environmental education, according to "Cameroun
Tribune" here today.
</P>
<P>
The reorientation of environmental education will involve
local communities through the promotion of conservation and
sustainable development practices.
</P>
<P>
Prior to this, the WWF has been active only in school systems
in the country. The new orientation reflects the WWF's policy to
make conservation practices more useful in terms of sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
The orientations will have two objectives: consolidating
on-going activities in formal educational systems and the new
initiatives at the community level.
</P>
<P>
Feasibility studies in this vein have already been carried out
by the WWF officials. It seeks to define the goal of the
orientation, and identify potential partners.
</P>
<P>
The report recalled that the environmental education was
introduced in Cameroun schools in 1995 by the WWF.
</P>
<P>
The Cameroun Environmental Education Network created in March
this year makes information on environmental education available
to all partners.
</P>
<P>
In April, a new environmental education initiative known as
the Cameroun environmental education support project was
introduced in the country to develop and promote environmental
education in schools and local communities. 
</P>
