<HEADLINE> Tung: HK People Confident of HK Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee-hwa, chief
executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region,
expressed here today confidence that Hong Kong will become an even
better place for its children and grandchildren as it is now
reunited with China.
</P>
<P>
"July 1, 1997 was a day to which we in Hong Kong had looked
forward with enormous pride and confidence," said Tung in a speech
at a luncheon hosted by the Asia Society in cooperation with the
Hong Kong Economic &AMP; Trade Office in New York, The Hong Kong
Association of New York, and the National committee on U.S.- China
Relations.
</P>
<P>
Tung, who is on a four-day visit to the United States, arrived
in New York last night to meet with representatives of the Chinese
society as well as economic and trade fields.
</P>
<P>
He said that there had been no change in the life style to
which Hong Kong people had been accustomed since the resumption of
China's sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1.
</P>
<P>
"Our economy continues to expand," he noted, adding that recent
surveys have shown 78 percent of the Hong Kong people are
confident of Hong Kong's future.
</P>
<P>
Responding to doubts of some Americans about the actual
implementation of the Basic Law, the Chief Executive said that the
doubts are "misguided."
</P>
<P>
"Clearly it is in China's basic national interest to ensure the
successful implementation of 'one country, two systems'," Tung
stressed. "If Hong Kong succeeds in our effort, we can contribute
towards continuing modernization of China."
</P>
<P>
He said that China's leadership is fully committed to making
"one country, two systems" a successful reality.
</P>
<P>
"They have complete faith in the ability of Hong Kong people
administering Hong Kong," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tung, who met some U.S. Congressmen in Washington earlier this
week, is scheduled to returned to the U.S. capital early Friday
morning before leaving home later on the day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
