<HEADLINE> U.S. Supports Military Measures on Algerian Militants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- the State Department, on
releasing a statement by its ambassador to Algeria, backing the
Algerian government to crack down Islamic militants, said on
Thursday that Washington supported the military measures.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued on Wednesday after Ambassador Ronald
Neumann made a farewell call on Algerian President Liamine Zeroual
in Algiers, condemned the "horrible massacres, bombings and
attacks on Algerian civilians" by the Islamic militants in the
country, calling it "an outrage to all civilized people."
</P>
<P>
"We support military measures, consistent with the rule of law,
to protect civilians," Neumann said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
At a regular briefing, State Department spokesman James Foley
re-stressed the U.S. support to the military measures "that are
consistent with the rule of law" to crack down the militants.
</P>
<P>
Another U.S. official, when asked about Neumann's statement,
said: "Any government is within its right, and we recognize that
right of a government, to protect its own people." 
</P>
