<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kashmir Issue High on Pak-Indian Talks Agenda: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The issue of Jammu and
Kashmir will be high on the agenda of the next round of foreign
secretary level talks starting next Monday between Pakistan and
India, a Foreign Office spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Having received "partially satisfactory" response about India's
conflicting statements, Pakistan agreed to take part in the third
round of foreign secretary level talks between the two countries
in the Indian capital New Delhi from September 15 to 18, the
spokesman announced at a news conference late this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad will proceed to New
Delhi next Monday for talks with his Indian counterpart, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming talks will "focus on the primacy of issues of
Jammu and Kashmir and peace and security", he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our main task at this round of talks is to operationalize the
mechanism as agreed in the Islamabad round of talks in June and
there is no need to repeat the most important issues on the agenda
are the Jammu and Kashmir and peace and security," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is absolutely no question of these issues not being on
the talks," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also emphasized the importance of continuing the
dialogue process with India, saying it is in the interest of
people in the region.
</P>
<P>
"Dialogue always help in solving problems, in removing the
mistrust and in seeking clarification. We need to do this in the
interest of people of this region," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If we want economic development, progress and prosperity in
this region, we must try to continue the dialogue in seeking just
and fair solution of the issues between us," he added.
</P>
<P>
"If we just remain stuck on these issues, how are we going to
seek progress, how are we going to reduce hostility?" the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and his Indian
counterpart I.K. Gujral, both of whom will go to New York for the
U.N. General Assembly meeting on September 22, will "very
hopefully" meet each other there.
</P>
<P>
The last round of foreign secretary level talks between the two
countries was held here in June. During the talks, the two sides
agreed to set up working groups to resolve their outstanding
issues including the dispute over Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and India resumed their foreign secretary level talks
in March this year after a suspension of more than three years
amid signs of improved relations between the two arch rivals in
South Asia.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have fought three wars since their
independence in 1947, two of which were over Kashmir that remains
to be a core issue in their bilateral relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
