<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Air-raid Opposition Stronghold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Afghan Taliban militia's
warplanes today bombed the opposition stronghold of
Mazar-e-Sharif, about 300 kilometers north of Kabul, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Taliban's warplanes bombed Afghanistan's second largest city in
the morning but there have been no reports of casualties in the
air raid.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, former Uzbek warlord Rashid Dostum, who was deposed
by his right-hand man Abdul Malik in late May, has reportedly
returned to Afghanistan after four months of exile in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Malik, who ousted Dostum in a surprise mutiny in May 19,
briefly sided with the Taliban, allowing them to enter northern
Afghanistan unopposed. However a few days later, in a row over
power sharing, Malik staged another about-face and drove the
student militia out again.
</P>
<P>
In the past four days, fighting has been continuing around
Mazar-e-Sharif between the Taliban and Malik's allied forces for
the control of the city.  
</P>
