<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Producer Prices Up 0.3 Percent in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Prices paid to U.S.
factories and other producers rose by a moderate 0.3 percent in
August, breaking an unprecedented string of seven monthly
declines, the U.S. Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the seasonally adjusted increase in the U.S.
Producer Price Index (PPI) for finished goods, prices paid by
wholesalers, was both the first and worst since a 0.5 percent rise
last December.
</P>
<P>
But even with the increase, the index still was falling at an
annual rate of 2.2 percent this year. It had posted declines
ranging from 0.1 percent to 0.5 percent from January through July,
the most consecutive drops since the government began compiling
the index in 1947.
</P>
<P>
Core prices, which excludes the volatile food and energy
sectors and is considered a better measure of price index in
wholesale level, increased just 0.1 percent in August after a
decline of the same amount in July.
</P>
<P>
The department said the increase of the PPI in August resulted
primarily from a 1.4 percent jump in energy prices and a 0.3
percent rise in foods.
</P>
<P>
Energy costs were led higher by a 5.9 percent jump in gasoline
prices, the largest in 16 months. Fuel oil rose 1.8 percent and
residential natural gas was up 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The increase of food prices resulted mainly from a 3.3 percent
gain in beef and veal prices and a 17.5 percent jump in fresh and
dry vegetables, the worst in 17 months.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) and the U.S. stock market have
been watching the PPI and other price measures closely for signs
that growing economy and low unemployment are pressuring business
to raise their prices faster than before.
</P>
<P>
But so far that hasn't happened. It permitted the U.S. Fed to
hold short-term interest rates steady since late March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0089 </DOCNO>
