<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Chief Urges Hungary to Proceed With Referendum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) Javier Solana has called
on Hungary to proceed with its planned referendum in order to
expedite its membership negotiation process.
</P>
<P>
A NATO press release today quoted Solana as saying the
referendum problem should be solved in the near future so that
"finalization of the (negotiation) process may take place before
the end of 1997."
</P>
<P>
The Hungarian parliament decided Tuesday to postpone
indefinitely the referendum on NATO membership, which had been
scheduled for November 16.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, however, NATO and Hungary began membership talks
in the alliance headquarters. In the first session of talks, NATO
explained to Hungarian officials the rights and obligations
resulting from accession to the bloc as well as the need to accept
the principles of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe and U.N. charters.
</P>
<P>
A NATO legal adviser also briefed the Hungarians on the status
of forces agreements, the agreement on the status of international
military headquarters in member countries and the status of staff
and delegations with NATO.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, which will close late next month, NATO and
Hungarian officials are also expected to discuss military issues
and financial resources.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, NATO is scheduled to start membership talks with
Poland next Tuesday and with the Czech Republic on September 23
respectively. Accession protocols are expected to be signed in
December this year.
</P>
<P>
The membership process will then go through ratification by the
legislative bodies of the three central and eastern European
countries as well as all the NATO member countries next year.
</P>
<P>
The three countries were invited to join the alliance at the
NATO Madrid summit held in early July.
</P>
<P>
The last accession protocol signed at NATO was that of Spain in
1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
