<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Satellite to Be Launched Late September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Satellite APSTAR-IIR, the
first Hong Kong satellite to be launched after its handover, is
expected to be put into orbit at the end of this month, it was
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
APSTAR-IIR is the third satellite procured by APT Satellite
Company Ltd. of Hong Kong, a company specializing in providing
satellite transponder services for communications and broadcasting
sectors in the Asia-Pacific region, including China.
</P>
<P>
The total sum insured for the whole launching project is around
220 million U.S. dollars, with the risk shared by major insurance
companies from both the Chinese mainland and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
An insurance policy signing and delivering ceremony for the
launch was jointly held today by APT, the People's Insurance
(Property) Company of China (PICC Property), Ming An Insurance
(HK) and Top Glory Insurance (Bermuda).
</P>
<P>
APSTAR-IIR is capable of covering more than 100 countries in
the entire Asia-Pacific region and majority part of Australia,
Europe and Africa with approximately 4 billion population, or 75
percent of the world's total, APT Vice Chairman and President He
Kerang said.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that the satellite and its launch vehicle, Long
March-3B, are at the final stage of the preparation for the
launch. The experts of the launch service provider, China Great
Wall Industry Corporation, are now at the launch site in Xichang,
Southwest China, conducting detailed test to prepare for the
forthcoming launch.
</P>
<P>
The APT has been providing services via two in-orbit
satellites, the APSTAR-I and APSTAR-IA. Over 90 percent of the
channels have been leased out.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stock Market Index Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Share prices in Hong Kong
stock market closed higher today after two straight days of sharp
declines.
</P>
<P>
Local stocks dived around midday after a relatively quiet
morning but rebounded in afternoon trading on a futures-led rally.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the Hang Seng Index, the market's key indicator of
blue chips, finished up 162.16 points, or 1.13 percent, to close
at 14,470.46.
</P>
<P>
Turnover reached 23.01 billion HK dollars (about 2.95 billion
U.S. dollars), up from Thursday's 21.08 billion HK dollars (about
2.7 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Analysts here attributed the rise to the speech of by Chinese
Communist Party leader Jiang Zemin at the party's 15th National
Congress earlier today in Beijing, pledging to speed up the reform
of state-run enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
