<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Government Signs Energy Contracts with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi government has
signed two commercial deals with two American companies, under
which a total of 240 million U.S. dollars would be invested in
this country's power and gas sectors, according to industry
sources.
</P>
<P>
In the first agreement signed on Thursday, UNOCAL, a major
American oil company, and Bangladesh's state-owned Petrobangla
initialed the approval of their production-sharing contract (PSC)
for the development of the Shahbajpur gas field in southeastern
Bhola district.
</P>
<P>
Energy Ministry and U.S. corporation Smith Congeneration signed
the other deal early this week for setting up a barge-mounted
power plant that Smith will install and operate at Haripur near
the capital Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
The UNOCAL will invest 50 million dollars in the first year of
the PSC and another 50 million dollars over the life of the
contract.
</P>
<P>
Under the PSC, the UNOCAL will deliver gas to the historically
under supplied western region of the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Smith Congeneration will invest approximately 140
million dollars to build the barge-mounted power station which it
will operate under the contract.
</P>
<P>
The power generation there will be sold to the Bangladesh Power
Development Board and help bridge this country's current energy
shortfall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
