<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hashimoto Reiterates Resolve to Carry Out Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto reiterated today his determination to carry out his
pledged reforms.
</P>
<P>
"I will proceed with the reforms with an indomitable resolve,"
Hashimoto said during a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, who was re-elected for his second two-year term as
president of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), named his
new cabinet Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for political leadership to successfully
implement his six pledged reforms, which include administrative,
fiscal, economic structure, social welfare, financial and
education reforms.
</P>
<P>
"To fulfill the reforms, I want to focus the imagination of all
persons connected with politics," he said.
</P>
<P>
To this end, Hashimoto added, the government will seek
cooperation with opposition parties on a policy-by-policy basis
while maintaining the tripartite coalition among the LDP and its
two non-cabinet parliamentary allies -- the Social Democratic
Party (SDP) and the New Party Sakigake.
</P>
<P>
On the diplomatic front, Hashimoto said he will make efforts to
further promote relations with China, Russia and South Korea,
while taking the Japan-U.S. ties as the basis.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto also defended his decision to name Koko Sato, a
veteran lawmaker convicted of taking bribes in the 1970s Lockheed
payoff scandal, as a minister despite criticism.
</P>
<P>
"I know there is criticism, but I reached the conclusion on
this selection after giving it repeated thought," Hashimoto said.
</P>
<P>
In Thursday's cabinet reshuffle, Sato was appointed as chief of
the Management and Coordination Agency, which is responsible for
administrative reform. This nomination received strong criticism
from opposition parties and LDP's non-cabinet allies.
</P>
<P>
Shigeru Lto, secretary-general of the SDP, told a party meeting
today that the public will lose its trust in administrative reform
because of Sato's appointment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
