<HEADLINE> Chinese Sailors Arrive at Colombo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-seven Chinese sailors
of the vessel Cordiality, which was attacked and damaged by Tamil
rebels Tuesday, arrived at Colombo at 5:45 p.m. local time today.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, 22 of the crew members will leave here for China
by air.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Hui and Zhang Yihua, two Chinese diplomats sent to
Pulmoddai to meet the crew following Tuesday's incident,
accompanied the 27 sailors to Colombo.
</P>
<P>
They left Habarana for Colombo at 2 p.m. The sailors were
transferred to this small town, 170 kilometers northeast of
Colombo, late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The captain, chief mate, second mate and two other sailors will
stay in Colombo. Later they will go back to Pulmoddai to look
after the damaged ship.
</P>
<P>
The tragic incident took place off Pulmoddai coast in
Trincomalee district at 1:30 a.m. Tuesday. A total of 32 Chinese
sailors were on board the ship, which was loading ilmenite sands
and scheduled to set sail 24 hours later.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan troops rescued 27 of the crew members. The other
five -- one from Hong Kong and four from China's inland areas --
are still missing.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side has asked the International Committee of the
Red Cross (ICRC) to contact the rebels on the recovery of those
missing.
</P>
<P>
MV Cordiality was the biggest foreign vessel so far attacked by
the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), who are fighting for
a separate state in Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
