<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Supports Ban on Commercial Whaling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian Environment
Minister Robert Hill today said Australia would oppose efforts by
Japan and Norway to encourage a resumption of whaling.
</P>
<P>
"We seek to put to them (Japan) the argument that one of the
most powerful economies on earth now doesn't really need to
continue whaling for scientific or any other purpose," Hill told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"We are very strongly of the view that commercial whaling is
now internationally unnecessary," he said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when commenting on the National Task Force
report on whaling, which was published ahead of the annual meeting
of the International Whaling Commission (IWC) scheduled from
October 20-24 in Monaco.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to protect the decreasing whale population, the
international community have been pushing for a ban on whaling,
while a few countries such as Japan want to resume whaling "for
scientific purpose".
</P>
<P>
The report recommends, among other things, efforts to push for
a global whale sanctuary and a permanent international ban on
commercial whaling.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government also supported the report's
recommendation to use existing bodies, particularly the IWC, to
develop a global sanctuary, the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
