<HEADLINE> Australia Detains Eight Thai, Indonesian Fishing Boats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Navy had
detained four Indonesian fishing boats and four Thai boats
illegally fishing in Australian waters, the Australian Associated
Press (AAP) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Andrew Reynolds, a defense department spokesman, was
quoted by AAP as saying two Australian patrol boats caught the
Thai and Indonesian boats in Australian waters around the Ashmore
Reef, about 800 kilometers west of Australia's port city of
Darwin, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The boats, which tried to outrun the patrol boats, were being
towed into Darwin today.
</P>
<P>
Three of the four Indonesian boats had satellite navigation
equipment, the other one was a 500-ton vessel, and they had a
total of 39 fishermen on board, the colonel said.
</P>
<P>
With no details about the Thai boats, the colonel said "I
believe it is the first time we've caught Thai fishing boats in
our waters."
</P>
<P>
AAP did not say whether the fishermen will be punished or not
for alleged illegal fishing in Australian waters.  
</P>
