<HEADLINE> France Hails Peace Gesture by Leah Rabin, Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 12 (Xinhua) -- France today hailed the gesture
for peace made by Leah Rabin, the widow of former Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin, and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Leah Rabin and Arafat jointly signed a communique expressing
the will for peace during a ceremony Thursday in the Palestinian
autonomous city of Ramallah in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was organized to mark the fourth anniversary of
the Oslo peace agreements between Israel and the Palestine
Liberation Organization (PLO).
</P>
<P>
"We have the greatest respect for the fight for peace of Madam
Rabin," French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said.
</P>
<P>
"It is touching that this high figure has chosen to appeal with
Yasser Arafat, the two peoples to pursue the road of peace."
</P>
<P>
The Oslo peace agreements, under which Israel and the PLO
recognized each other, were signed by Yitzhak Rabin and Arafat at
the White House on September 14, 1993.
</P>
<P>
Rabin was assassinated by an Israeli extreme right wing
activist in November 1995 in Tel Aviv. His widow, Leah Rabin, has
since served as a moral pillar for the Israeli left wing Labor
Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
