<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK Hands Over U.S. Soldier Remains at Panmunjom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 12 (Xinhua) -- the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea today handed over the remains of a U.S. soldier killed in the
1950-53 Korean War through the truce village Panmunjom.
</P>
<P>
The remains were recovered less than one kilometers from the
Unsan village in North Pyongan Province by a joint U.S.-DPRK team.
</P>
<P>
Unsan was the scene of fierce fighting between Chinese
Volunteers' forces and the U.S. Army's 8th Cavalry in the fall of
1950, a spokesman of the U.S. Army Forces in Seoul said.
</P>
<P>
Last month, in a search at a different site, four sets of
remains were found. They are undergoing forensic analysis at the
U.S. Army's Central Identification Laboratory in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
The United States and DPRK have agreed to excavate the remains
of U.S. soldiers on three occasions this year. DPRK delivered the
remains of 210 U.S. soldiers to the United States between 1990 and
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
