<HEADLINE> Mandela Pays Tribute to Black Acitivist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela today spoke highly of Black Consciousness leader
Steve Biko who fought against apartheid before he was harassed to
death on September 12, 1977.
</P>
<P>
Unveiling a bronze bust of Biko at a cemetery where he was
buried in King William's Town, East Cape province, Mandela said
"he (Biko) impressed us so much that we came to believe that Biko
was as old as the mountains."
</P>
<P>
The cemetery, barren and dusty tract of land next to a railway
station on the outskirts of King William's town, was renamed the
Steve Biko garden of remembrance.
</P>
<P>
South African parliament unanimously agreed on Thursday to a
motion, saying it recognized Biko's contribution to the struggle
for freedom and the fight against apartheid. 
