<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank, IMF Update Schedule of Annual Meetings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The updated schedule of
events was unveiled today for the upcoming World Bank and
international Monetary Fund (IMF) Annual Meetings, to be held here
between September 23 and 25.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of 181 members of the two organizations will
take part in the Meetings, the most prestigious annual event in
the international financial community.
</P>
<P>
The list of official delegates will be released early next
week, said Merrell Tuck-Primdahl, media information officer of
the World Bank, at a news briefing here today.
</P>
<P>
The meetings, hosted by China in the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR), are widely believed as a vote of
confidence of the World Bank and the IMF in Hong Kong's economic
strength after July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to the scheduled program released today, Chinese
Premier Li Peng will address the opening ceremony, along with Hong
Kong SAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa, World Bank President James
D. Wolfensohn and IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus. Annual
discussions on world economy will go on through the following
sessions.
</P>
<P>
Before the Meetings, the Program of Seminars, a forum for
business leaders, government delegates, senior World Bank and IMF
officials to exchange views on development in emerging economies,
will take place. This year's theme is on Asia and the
World: Capital, Competitiveness and Community.
</P>
<P>
Starting from September 20, the four-day program of seminars
will present a wide range of perspectives in areas such as finance
and capital markets, infrastructure development, regional and
country opportunities and sustainable growth.
</P>
<P>
A special seminar on "Asia and the IMF" will be held on
September 19, focusing on themes relevant to the region's economic
performance and outlook, as well as the macroeconomic surveillance
role the IMF has played.
</P>
<P>
Surrounding the Annual Meetings, the World Bank has released a
number of reports, including Poverty in Asia, Finance in Asia, and
Global Economic Prospects. Tim Cullen, senior advisor of the World
Bank, said that more will come out, including reports on
infrastructure development, South Asia, and China. IMF will
release an important report on World Economic Outlook on September
17.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 10,000 participants, including finance
ministers and central bank governors, representatives from
international and regional organizations and business
leaders. Some 2,000 journalists from around the world are expected
to come for the event.  
</P>
</TEXT>
