<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Philippine Economy Slides Amid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
scaled down its gross national product (GNP) growth target for the
year to above 5.6 percent amid prolonged volatility in Southeast
Asian currency markets.
</P>
<P>
Economic Development Secretary Cielito Habito said the
adjustment was made after his office computed how much the
financial turmoil had adversely affected the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Amid the currency woes sweeping the region, the peso has fallen
by 22 percent in the past two months, fluctuating around one U.S.
dollar to 32.3 pesos at present. The local stock market was also
trapped in the turmoil, breaking the record low of 2,000 points
late last month.
</P>
<P>
Habito said the new GNP growth target was down from the target
of 7-8 percent the government set earlier, but he added that the
country does not have to downscale its domestic growth as
dramatically as Thailand, whose gross domestic product (GDP) is
expected to grow between 1 and 2 percent only.
</P>
<P>
GDP is the sum of goods and services produced in a country
while GNP is the country's total value of goods and services and
foreign income.
</P>
<P>
Although the government said the Philippines' economic
fundamentals were sound, economists believed that the economic
situation could get worse, taking into account the weakening of
the peso and the harm of high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of the year, the economy has already signaled
a slowdown for the whole year. The GNP and GDP grew 5.9 percent
and 5.3 percent respectively, down from 7.5 percent and 5.7
percent in the same period last year. Poor industrial and
agricultural growth and a sharp decline in overseas workers'
remittance were attributed to the poor economic performance.
</P>
<P>
It was at this time that the financial turbulence spilled over
to the country from Thailand. Economists were convinced that the
unrest would accelerate the slowdown of the Philippine economy.
</P>
<P>
To stabilize the peso, the Central Bank sold U.S. dollars and
hiked banks' liquidity reserve rate among other measures. However,
the efforts did not arrest the peso from falling. Instead, it
triggered a crisis of confidence. Foreign investors pulled their
funds out of the country amid fears that economic growth and
political situation are becoming unstable in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The situation worsened as President Fidel Ramos failed to
clarify that he would not seek a second term. The businessmen
community had complained that Ramos has talked too much about
changing the charter to extend his term rather than focusing on
developing the economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, interest rates in the country soared to five-year
highs. The benchmark 91-day Treasury bill rate and banks' prime
lending rates reached 19 percent and 30 percent respectively
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The monetary authorities later stopped intervening in the
foreign exchange trading and reduced the liquidity reserve rate
from 8 to 6 percent, but the economy had already felt the pinch.
</P>
<P>
High interest rates made it harder for companies to get the
cash they needed to do business or to expand production.
Economists believed that the manufacturing industry, which has
already been in recession, was afflicted the most by the high
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The weakening of peso also pushed up the prices of basic goods
and oil products and power rates, eroding consumers' spending
power while making the country's foreign debt bigger. All these
factors may spell a disaster for the economy.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the agricultural sector, which accounts for 20
percent of the GDP, would not garner a bumper harvest as it did
last year. The sector grew by 4 percent in 1996 after bad weather
sent its growth to almost zero level at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, economists predicted that the Philippine economy
would slide further in the second half of the year. They estimated
that the country's GDP would grow by 5 percent this year, lower
than the 5.5 percent registered last year and the 6.3 to 7 percent
planned by the government.
</P>
<P>
To revive the economic growth, the government has outlined
urgent measures to cut down cost of production, minimize price
hikes of consumer goods, enhance the efficiency of key economic
sectors such as agriculture, power and finance, and improve the
government's revenue base.
</P>
<P>
But economists still believed that the economy would remain
weak until 1998, even the first half of 1999, as the financial
unrest in the region would continue for three to six months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Says It Does Not Want Cold Relations With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 12 (Xinhua) -- France does not want a "cold"
relationship with Israel, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said just
one day after Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine made an
unprecedented attack on the Israeli policy toward the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"There should be no coldness between France and Israel. Nothing
should harm the traditional friendship and cooperation that France
has with Israel," said the spokesman, Jacques Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
He said it is out of friendship that France expresses its
worries about the situation in the Middle East, adding that "to
talk about these things should not be considered negative."
</P>
<P>
Rummelhardt said, "the degradation of the peace process should
not justify the least tolerance or indulgence in respect of
terrorism."
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said Thursday at a Socialist Party conference that the
policy of the Israeli government toward the Palestinians is
"catastrophic" as it has driven Palestinians "to the level of
exasperation and despair without precedent."
</P>
<P>
The accusation was rejected by both Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Foreign Minister David Levy, who blamed
Vedrine for mentioning nothing about the terrorism that has struck
Israel. 
</P>
