<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: Future Visists Depend on Hard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 12 (Xinhua) -- United States Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright said today that she would return to
the region only if both Israeli and Palestinian leaders
"have made hard decisions" to advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Albright made the remarks in the West Bank city of Ramallah
after her second meeting with Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat. Both leaders described today's meeting
as "good" and "constructive," but they still fell short of
announcing any major breakthrough in resuming the stalled
Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Albright admitted that she was unable to make great progress
toward a resumption of the peace talks between the Israelis and
Palestinians. "I will not come back to tread the water," she said
at a press conference after the meeting with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The only concrete result was Albright's announcement that
senior aides to Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu would travel to Washington late this month to continue
talks on advancing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
This announcement appeared to be aimed at avoiding the
impression that Albright's first visit here has been a total
failure, an assessment that could threaten to increase the
tensions between Israel and Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Albright and Arafat held their first meeting Thursday to
discuss ways of breaking the prolonged deadlock in the peace
process caused by Israel's building of the Har Homa settlement
and aggravated by the recent wave of suicide bombings in
Jerusalem launched by the Palestinian militant group the Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas).
</P>
<P>
Israel has conditioned the resumption of the peace process on
the PNA's actions to launch an all-out war against Islamic
militant groups and their infrastructure. The PNA, for its part,
demanded Israel lift the total closure of its territories,
releasing the frozen funds and other sanctions.
</P>
<P>
In a direct public appeal to the Palestinians broadcasted by
the Voice of Palestine today, Albright urged the PNA to crack
down on Hamas and another militant anti-Israeli group the
Islamic Jihad. She also called for the Palestinian public
support in the fight against terrorism, because "the average
Palestinian has no greater enemy than Islamic Jihad and Hamas."
</P>
<P>
"That is why fighting terrorism is the responsibility of both
the Palestinian Authority and the Palestinian people, and that
is why all must understand that the battle against terrorism is
in the interests of the Arabs, Palestinians and Israelis," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who is striving to narrow the huge gap between the
parties, has already held two rounds of talks with Netanyahu in
the first two days of her three-day visit here.
</P>
<P>
So far there was no sign that she has made any major progress
in getting the peace process back on track. She said there was
still a long way to go to rebuild the mutual trust and
confidence in order to revive and advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side has been critical of Albright's
one-sided attitude even since the beginning of her mission
here. In an arriving statement made after meeting with Israeli
President Ezer Weizman Wednesday, she stressed the U.S.
unequivocal support to Israel's insistence on the PNA's promise
to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Only in a speech at an Israeli school Thursday evening,
Albright criticized Israel for taking unilateral steps to
preempt the final-status talks with Palestine, including building
settlements, confiscating Palestinian land and demolishing
Palestinian houses.
</P>
<P>
Despite the criticism, Israeli officials did not interpret
it as Albright's presure on Israel to lift its demands on the
Israel to stop the sanctions and freeze the settlement
activities.
</P>
<P>
Late today, Albright is to travel to Syria at the second leg
of her first Middle East trip which will also take her to Egypt,
Jordan and Saudi Arabia. In Damascus, she is to explore with
Syrian President Hafez al-Assad ways to resume the suspended peace
talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel's TV reported that she would carry a written message
from Israeli officials, but gave no details. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
