<HEADLINE> Australia To Hold Constitutional Convention In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Australians will decide
whether Australia should become a republic during a two-week
constitutional convention in February.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard told reporters in Sydney today the
convention would be held at the old parliament house in Canberra
on February 2-6 and February 9-13, Australian Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
The 152 delegates at the convention will decide if the
Australian constitution should be changed to create a republic,
which model would be the best, and a timetable for change.
</P>
<P>
Half of the delegates are to be elected while the another half
appointed.
</P>
<P>
A formal notice for the election of the 76 elective convention
delegates by non-compulsory secret postal ballot will be issued on
September 29 with nominations closing on October 8 and ballot
papers distributed between November 3 and 14.
</P>
<P>
The poll will close on December 9, according to a timetable
released today by the prime minister's office.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll published early this week showed that a little
more than 50 percent among Australians support a republic,
however, the prime minister said he believed there would still be
many issues to resolve before the change could happen.
</P>
<P>
"I think we have a long way to go and certain issues to
resolve, but at the end of the day the people will determine this
and not on opinion polls," he said.
</P>
<P>
"They will determine it through their election of delegates,
through the attitudes taken at the convention and ultimately
through a vote, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
