<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scots Strongly Favor U.K. Devolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Scotland, backed by an
overwhelming majority of its voters, is to have its own parliament
for the first time in nearly 300 years.
</P>
<P>
Official ballot results released early today showed that 74.3
percent of Scottish voters support home rule, a figure that far
exceeded expectations of pro-devolution campaigners.
</P>
<P>
Voters in only two councils opposed giving the legislative
assembly, which will control a 14-billion-pound (22.4 billion
U.S. dollars) budget, powers to decide on taxation.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's vote is seen as the climax of a century-long
campaign for home rule and is expected to be the most far-reaching
change in Scotland's relations with the rest of the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Legislation establishing the Scottish parliament still has yet
to go through the U.K. parliament next year.
</P>
<P>
But the decisive vote means that elections for a 129-member
parliament, under a system of proportional representation, will
take place in 1998 and it will get down to work the following year.
</P>
<P>
The proposals for a Scottish parliament and a less powerful
assembly in Wales are central to the British Labor government's
plans for reform of the U.K. constitution.
</P>
<P>
In a statement after hearing the early result, Prime Minister
Tony Blair said he was "absolutely delighted that the Scottish
people have backed our plans." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Refuses to Scrap Trade Pacts with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by liu Yegang)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has
strongly defended the string of trade arrangements with its
neighbors, saying these accords will remain until an effective
multilateral deal is in place in the region.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by Mfundo Nkuhlu, Director of African
Trade Relations at the Ministry of Trade and Industry, local
media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Scrapping existing pacts before a multinational dealis in
place is meant to ask South Africa's neighbors to give up a bird
in hand for one in the bush, he said.
</P>
<P>
The agreements, signed during the apartheid years, came under
fire recently when Kaire Mbuende, Executive Secretary of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC), urged the body's
members to scrap them as they perpetuated inequities.
</P>
<P>
Mbuende's call marked a shift in the SADC's official line
which has so far tolerated the deals.
</P>
<P>
It came amid internal criticism in South Africa of
government's bid to negotiate a preferential trade deal with its
partners in the Southern African Customs Union on the one hand,
and Zambia on the other.
</P>
<P>
The union was formed during apartheid era and all of its
members are now belonging to the SADC.
</P>
<P>
The SADC, which admitted two new members -- Seychelles and the
Democratic Republic of Congo this week, is planning to free all
trade exchanges by 2004.
</P>
<P>
Nkuhlu said if the SADC free trade protocol is comprehensive
enough by 2004, there will be no need for bilateral agreements.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, talks to grant improved market
access for Zimbabwean farm and certain manufacturing items are
under way. The clothing and textile preferential access
arrangement with Harare is being implemented.
</P>
<P>
South Africa and customs union signatories Botswana, Lesotho,
Namibia and Swaziland, will soon hold talks with Zambia to
respond to the latter's request for concessionary market access
on a range of products, Nkuhlu said.
</P>
<P>
Pretoria will offer its SADC partners duty-free access within
five years, according to Nkuhlu.
</P>
<P>
But he said South Africa's customs union partners, who share
the same external tariffs systems, will be allowed to seek
reciprocity from other SADC partners.
</P>
<P>
The arrangement will benefit South Africa's relatively weaker
partners in the union, who could then guarantee potential
investors duty-free access to the rest of the SADC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
