<HEADLINE> India Wanted to Test Hydrogen Bomb in 1970s: Press </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Indian nuclear scientists
wanted to test a hydrogen bomb shortly after they exploded a
plutonium device in 1974 but were stopped by the government, the
Press Trust of India (PTI) said today.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Padmanabha Krishnagopala Iyengar, former
chairman of the Indian Atomic Energy Commission and one of the
prominent scientists involved in the design of the country's first
nuclear bomb.
</P>
<P>
"There was so much euphoria after the first successful nuclear
test, it would have been the best time for testing the hydrogen
device," Iyengar told newsmen here in an informal chat early this
week at the conference on "The Role of Nuclear Energy in
Sustainable Development", the PTI said.
</P>
<P>
Some government advisers warned the then prime minister, Indira
Gandhi, of adverse international reactions. One of them said that
Air India would not be able to fly its planes because it would be
denied spare parts, the PTI quoted Iyengar as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to Iyengar, the hydrogen test could have pushed India
closer to being declared a weapon power instead of being placed in
the current situation where it is neither here nor there.
</P>
</TEXT>
