<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Idea of Housing prisoners in Ships Being </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's
Correctional Service Department has put the idea of mine shaft
jails on hold, but is still keen on introducing prison ships,
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The idea of using disused mine shafts for the country's most
dangerous prisoners has been shelved for the time being because
the investigation takes too long, Minister of the Correctional
Service Department Sipo Mzimela was quoted as reporting.
</P>
<P>
Referring to prison ships which has been proved highly
successful in the United States and Britain, Mzimela said the
investigation of prison ships is still at the preliminary stage.
</P>
<P>
Correctional Service Department sources said that if private
enterprise can house prisoners in ships at cost that compared
with the Prisons Departemnt's 70 Rand (14 U.S. Dollars) a day a
prisoner, prison ships will be considered.
</P>
<P>
Mzimela held taht prison ships can be anchored in small
harbors off South Africa's eastern coastline.
</P>
<P>
"On the Indian ocean side, there are lots of sharks. They will
serve as our front line defense against escapes, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Due to corruption among prision officials, the number of
prison escapes in South Africa remained fairly constant at about
100 a month for a number of years. A campaign is under way to cut
by at least 50 percent with a year.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, facing high level of violent crimes, has been
troubled with rapid growing prison population. Compared with
125,000 prisoners at the end of December last year, the prison
population is more than 135,000 at present, Mzimela said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
