<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Port Of Entry On Sino-Russian Border Becomes National Model </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Reform measures have improved
the inefficiency of the Dongning Port of Entry on the Sino-Russian
border and have even made it a national model.
</P>
<P>
It used to be plagued by bad management, but it managed to turn
itself around so well that it was called a "civilized advanced
port of entry" by central government authorities recently, and
handled a record 130,000 tons of cargo and 70,000 passengers in
the January-August period.
</P>
<P>
Because of bad management it previously suffered from slow
business and poor customs declaration and processing methods, but
with new practices, vehicles leaving China can be checked in
warehouses before passing through the port. And vehicles entering
China can pass the outlet first before going to warehouses for
inspection.
</P>
<P>
In order to facilitate fruit and vegetable exports, a unified
examination has been designed for the warehouses, helping reduce
waiting time and avoiding spoilage.
</P>
<P>
The use of computers has also helped eliminate paper work and
improve efficiency. The port has also introduced 24-hour service
to cater to the clients' needs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> River Quality in Malaysia Deteriorates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The river quality in
Malaysia deteriorated last year due to soil erosion and organic
pollutant from partially treated sewage and animal wastes,
according to the 1996 Environmental Quality Report released today.
</P>
<P>
During the year, 57 major rivers in the country were found to
be heavily polluted by suspended solids from earthworks and land
clearing, of which 38 had deteriorated, the report released by the
Department of Environment (DOE) said.
</P>
<P>
The DOE report said that other sources of river pollution were
agro-based, manufacturing, livestock farming and domestic waste
and added 15 river catchments were heavily polluted from these
sources, with eight of them having deteriorated further than
previous years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 34 percent of organic loading into the river were
contributed by livestock farming and domestic waste and the number
of river catchments which were highly polluted by these sources
were 38, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the marine environmental quality in
the country last year improved compared to 1995.
</P>
<P>
It said that as in previous years, the main contaminants of the
coastal waters in all states of the country were oil and grease,
total suspended solids (TSS) and "Escherichia coli".
</P>
<P>
Last year, a total of 597 samples were collected from 202
marine monitoring stations, compared to 557 samples from 186
monitoring stations in 1995, the report said, adding that almost
72 percent of the total number of monitoring stations were
polluted by oil and grease, 54 percent by TSS and 30 percent by
Escherichia coli.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the Department also established the
Ground water Monitoring Reporting Network in peninsular Malaysia
last year to evaluate the status and extent of ground water
contamination throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The network is also aimed at identifying sites with high risk
of ground water contamination caused by human activities and
designing a network of monitoring wells.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the DOE places great priority on
complaints received from the public, through the mass-media, from
relevant agencies, non-governmental bodies as well as individuals
on pollution.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 3,177 complaints were received by the DOE where 75
percent or 2,382 were complaints on air pollution, 347 or 11
percent on water.
</P>
<P>
In respect of water pollution complaints, analysis showed that
non-industrial sources, palm oil mills, feed mills, food and
beverage industries and sewage were major contributors to water
pollution, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It also said that from 256 cases prosecuted last year under the
Environmental Quality Act (EQA) passed in 1974, 1.18 million
ringgit (about 0.4 million U.S. dollars) was collected as fines,
an increase of 132 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the DOE is considering setting up a
multipurpose airborne surveillance program to monitor the
pollution of air, water and marine.
</P>
<P>
The existing joint airborne surveillance program between the
DOE and the Police Air Wing had shown success in providing useful
and speedy surveillance information on activities violating the
EQA.
</P>
<P>
The report said airborne surveillance on pollution activities
were carried out in the states of Selangor, Negeri Sembilan,
Melaka, Johor, Pahang and in the capital city of Kuala Lumpur to
detect excessive smoke emission from industries, open burning such
as at dumping grounds and forest fires.
</P>
<P>
The report said the aerial surveillance helped to strengthen
ground enforcement on open burning and stack emissions from
industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Agriculture Ministers Vow to Protect Sea Turtles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Ministers of agriculture and
forestry from nine ASEAN nations signed here today a memorandum of
understanding (MOU) on the conservation and protection of sea
turtles.
</P>
<P>
The document is aimed at indicating ASEAN's concern on this
environment-related issue and expressing its "firm stand and
integrated effort to protect and conserve sea turtles vis-a-vis
its endeavors to expand the region's shrimp export to the global
market," a press release of the meeting said.
</P>
<P>
The MOU was signed at the end of the two-day 19th meeting of
the ministers of agriculture and forestry of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
In the light of the current global challenges to make the
agriculture and forestry sectors more competitive while
maintaining the sustainability of the region's natural resources,
the ministers agreed to strengthen future regional cooperation in
food, agriculture and forestry in line with the ASEAN vision for
the next century.
</P>
<P>
For this purpose, the ministers approved the establishment of
an ASEAN shrimp industry task force to draw up a regional policy
aimed at maximizing shrimp production at the lowest costs and in
the most environmentally-friendly manner.
</P>
<P>
The meeting endorsed a "manual on good shrimp farm management
practices" for distribution among ASEAN nations.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also agreed to increase cooperation on the
establishment of information networks and development of regional
strategy and policy options on environment and conservation issues
related to trade in agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also discussed some other issues such as animal
vaccines, promotion and falling prices of natural rubber and
reduction of pesticide use.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also welcomed the private sector to take an active
part in the fields of agriculture, fishery and forestry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
