<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swaziland Accuses S. Africa of Meddling Internal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The one-party Swaziland
parliament has bitterly blamed South African President Nelson
Mandela for allegedly "meddling in Swaziland's internal affairs".
</P>
<P>
The attack on Mandela by angry parliament members in both the
House of Assembly and the Senate Thursday night was in support of
King Mswati III, who rejected Mandela's accusations in his speech
made at the summit of the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) held in Blantyre, Malawi on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, chairman of the regional body, at the summit called
on countries in the region to promote democratic process.
</P>
<P>
The king said on his return from the summit that the SADC is
being mis-informed by certain organisations in his country that
want to impose their own brand of democracy on the Swazi people.
</P>
<P>
Leading Thursday's attack on Mandela, staunch traditionalist
parliament member Mgabhi Dlamini said, the South African
President appeared to have "undeclared interest in Swaziland".
</P>
<P>
Mandela "should not think that Swaziland was part of South
Africa", Dlamini claimed.
</P>
<P>
However, Mandela's attack on traditionalist leaders who "deny
real democracy to their countries", widely interpreted to be a
reference to Swaziland's authoritarian monarchy, were also
praised in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Joshua Mzizi, secretary of the Human Rights Association based
in Mbabane, praised Mandela's criticism of restrictive
traditional political system.
</P>
<P>
Mandela had shown that the SADC did not consist only of
"buddies", he said, but "serious leaders whose vision is the
vision for all humanity". 
</P>
</TEXT>
