<HEADLINE> Former Seoul Mayor Facing Hard Work in Pursuing Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Nominated Thursday as candidate
of the small opposition Democratic Party (DP), former Seoul Mayor
Cho Soon joined the presidential race with many difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The first task facing Cho, now as the DP's president, seems to
be to inject fresh life into the party which has been sidelined
from the center of the country's political stage, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Cho is planning to reshape the party and bring
political outsiders in to support him, party sources said.
</P>
<P>
The latest opinion poll put Cho behind Kim Dae-jung of the main
opposition National Congress for New Politics (NCNP) and Lee
Hoi-chang of the ruling New Korea Party (NKP).
</P>
<P>
Aware of his disadvantage, Cho said he would join hands with
other political groups opposing the two leading candidates.
</P>
<P>
There has been media reports that Cho may seek an alliance with
the NKP's Rhee In-je, who resigned from Governor of Kyonggi
Province Monday and is considering running in the election.
</P>
<P>
However, the expected negotiations between Cho and Rhee over
one ticket may face the problem that neither will give up their
presidential ambitions, observers said.
</P>
<P>
Along with his efforts to join hands with certain political
groups, Cho is expected to go all-out to recruit prominent figures
from various walks of life to reinforce the party.
</P>
<P>
Aides to Cho said he has already received promises from some
100 people, including scholars and lawyers, to join the party.
</P>
<P>
Another task facing Cho is to unite his own party members.
</P>
<P>
Cho is planning a major reshuffle of top party officeholders to
facilitate the admission of the Council for National Unification
(CNU) into his party.
</P>
<P>
He is reportedly considering allocating some key posts to CNU
members, who left the party after feuding with former DP leader
Lee Ki-taek last year but support Cho's presidential candidacy.
</P>
<P>
But observers say such efforts will be rewarded only when
followers of Lee Ki-taek support Cho.
</P>
<P>
Cho's aides remain concerned that the faction led by Lee
Ki-taek may challenge the candidate as they fear losing their
posts in the party's new line-up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
