<HEADLINE> Britain Calls for More Sanctions on Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain called for wider
sanctions on Nigeria Thursday at the opening of the Commonwealth
Ministerial Action Group (CMAG) in London, local media reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Britain appealed to the eight-member CMAG to
continue Nigeria's suspension from the the 53-nation group, but
stopped short of asking for its expulsion, as is the speculation
by some people.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is now sanctioned by Britain, the European Union,
Canada and Jamaica for the annulment of the June 12, 1993
election. It was suspended from the commonwealth in late 1995 for
executing author Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other Ogoni activists.
</P>
<P>
Britain Thursday voiced its anger that a significant number of
Commonwealth countries primarily from Africa have failed to adopt
stringent measures against Nigeria, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The two-day CMAG meeting will make a recommendation to the
summit of Commonwealth leaders in Edinburgh, Scotland, in
October.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe that continued suspension is the most likely
choice for the Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
The same fate is likely to fall to Sierra Leone, which was
suspended from the Commonwealth following the May 25 coup that
overthrew elected President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
