<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reform Proposals in Kenya Praised by Opposition Parties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 12 (Xinhua) -- "History is Made" and
"History in the Making" are the front page titles of today's
Kenya Time and East African Standard in praise of the
just-adopted wide-ranging reform proposals.
</P>
<P>
The proposals made by three technical committees were
unanimously adopted here Thursday at the third plenary session of
the Inter-Party Parliamentary Group (IPPG).
</P>
<P>
The IPPG resolved that the proposed changes in the
Constitution, legal and administrative reforms, the Electoral
Code and peace and security should be immediately translated into
Bills and brought to Parliament for enactment.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, 132 Members of Parliament from the ruling
Kenya African National Union (KANU) and Opposition agreed to
amend or repeal 12 colonial-era laws within a month.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed that President Daniel arap Moi should appoint
10 more commissioners to the Electoral Commission to make it
"independent and impartial".
</P>
<P>
Before the plenary session, Moi said the IPPG had reached a
consensus in the true African style and spirit when he met the
IPPG Co-ordinated Committee on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that if all Kenyans put the wider interests of
their country first, then all institutions will function
effectively.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the proposed changes, Vice-President George
Saitoti said IPPG proposals are the greatest achievement made by
the Seventh Parliament.
</P>
<P>
When the history of the country will finally be written, the
IPPG initiative and the efforts of the three technical committees
will be recognized, he added.
</P>
<P>
Nicholas Biwott, who is believed to be a hardliner on
constitutional reforms, said in a statement that the IPPG
meetings between the KANU and opposition parties are an
indication that Kenyans can solve teething constitutional
problems in an atmosphere of peace and justice.
</P>
<P>
Michael Wamalwa, leader of the official opposition in
parliament, described the reform talks as "historic", saying that
the IPPG had helped "to write Kenya's history in golden letters".
</P>
<P>
Speaker Francis Ole Kaparo noted at the meeting that yesterday
is the happiest day of his life as his dream of bringing
Opposition and the ruling KANU MPs into talks had been realized.
</P>
<P>
The excited Speaker noted that he felt his mission to bring
both sides of the house together had ultimately succeeded
following the outcome of the talks.
</P>
<P>
The proposed changes are also praised by opposition leaders
such as Mwai Kibaki, Chairman of Democratic Party, and Martin
Shikuku, Ford-Asili Secretary General.
</P>
<P>
Kibaki pointed out that the MPs being present at the meeting
confounded sceptics by the success they had achieved, adding that
the success is the first step towards the formulation of a good
constitution for the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the opposition Ford-Asili Chairman Kenneth Matiba
dismissed IPPG recommendations Thursday night, saying that its
views can not represent the majority of Kenyan people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
