<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Cabinet Demands for Right to Import </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The South African
cabinet should be in a position to take decisions on the proposed
armaments package deals by early next year, local daily The
Citizen quoted a senior official as reporting today.
</P>
<P>
Several countries are "queuing up" with proposals to suppy
South Africa with corvettes, submarines, warplanes and
helicopters, Deputy Defense Minister Ronnie Kasrils said in Cape
Town Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Some western countries, including Britain, Germany and Spain,
have been trying to sell packages of weapons to the South African
National Defense Force, which complains that some key arms in use
are either obsolete or in poor condition.
</P>
<P>
The packages being looked at are not simply the acquisition of
arms, but involved favorable counter-trade,long-term-low-interest
loans, investments, joint manufacturing projects, technology
exchange and other partnership proposals, Kasril said.
</P>
<P>
Urgent negotiations with various countries are well under way
and South Africa can not afford to drag its feet, he said, adding
that his country has to show its seriousnes to potential
partners, or they may lose interest.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that the Defense Ministry's view regarding the
urgency of the situation has been shared by the departments of
trade and industry, and finance, as well as Deputy President
Thabo Mbeki. 
</P>
</TEXT>
