<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Total Lunar Eclipse For China's Mid-Autumn Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- A total lunar eclipse will
occur late on the night of China's traditional Mid-Autumn Festival
(September 16), when they have had a full day of moon-cakes, the
traditional festival delicacy, and a full moon in the night.
</P>
<P>
The occurrence will make this year's Festival more interesting
than usual because Chinese regard a full moon as a symbol of the
happiness of having the family members all together.
</P>
<P>
This is a rare total lunar eclipse, according to He Yunan,
associate research fellow with the Chinese Academy of Sciences'
Zijinshan (Purple Mountain) Observatory in Nanjing, the capital of
Jiangsu province.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese can enjoy the full moon before midnight on the
festival and observe the changes of the moon when the eclipse
takes place later," she explained.
</P>
<P>
The eclipse will begin at 1:08 am and end at 4:25 (Beijing
time), September 17, and can be seen worldwide, she said. The next
similar lunar eclipse will occur during the Mid-Autumn Festival in
the year 2062. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
