<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Threatens to Quit SADC Leadership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela had threatened to quit being head of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) due to sharp differences
with his Zimbabwean counterpart Robert Mugabe over security
issues, local daily Business Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
The tensions stem from difference between Mandela and Mugabe
on the status of the SADC's potentially powerful subcommittee on
defense, politics and security, which is chaired by the latter.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources who declined to be named, said the
subcommittee's activities were suspended last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who chairs the SADC, believed that the subcommittee
is an integral part of the organization instead of a paralleled
organization, and that the SADC chairman should also head the
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, however, insisted that more independent role should be
granted to the institution, which should have right to hold a
separate summit from the main SADC summit in much the same way as
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization operates, said the report
quoting the sources.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Financial Gazette reported Thursday that Mandela
had made "his bullying threat" to resign at the weekend. On
Wednesday, Herald, Zimgbabwe's government-controlled newspaper,
claimed that a "power struggle" had been erupted between
Mandela and Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
But Mandela's spokesman Parks Mankahlana denied allegations
that South Africa would withdraw its membership from the SADC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multinational To Go Looking for Gold in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 12 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Western Mining
Corp. Holdings Ltd. is expected to spend 29 million US dollars
prospecting for gold in Yili Prefecture, in northwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
"We have been considering this project for nearly three years,"
said Dr. John Parry, the company's deputy general manager, "Our
experts have done on-the-spot investigations in Yili many times,
and made sure that the prefecture has good prospects of gold
reserves, and expect to find gold mines in 3-5 years for
large-scale mining."
</P>
<P>
This will be one of the company's four major projects in the
world. It is the world's eighth largest mining company, with
nearly 10 billion US dollars worth of assets.
</P>
<P>
"My company has shown great concern to the local investment
climate, and invited Dr. Stephen Fitzgerald, the first Australian
ambassador to China, to serve as an advisor for this effort. So we
think Yili's social order, natural environment, and communications
are all suitable for investment," Parry said.
</P>
<P>
He also spoke well of his Chinese counterparts' work and said
the project had the most rapid co-operation of any outside
Australia.
</P>
<P>
Parry signed a contract with the No. 305 Project Office, which
is responsible for state verification of distribution of mineral
resources in Xinjiang. The agreement calls for prospecting in
Yili's Tulasu Basin, where the company will spend four million US
dollars on the first phase, and another 25 million on the second
phase.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, nearly 30 groups have visited Xinjiang
and talked with their counterparts about prospecting. The US's
Barrick Power Co. began prospecting last year in the region.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang has six mineral areas and is especially rich in gold,
nickel, and copper reserves. The Tianshan Mountains in Yili are
one of the best areas for prospecting, according to Wang Futong,
chief engineer of the region's Geology and Mineral Resources
Department.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
