<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Increases Tea Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's tea exports by the
major exporting companies have risen from one million kilograms
in March to 1.6 million kg in June this year, reported the local
daily The New Vision today.
</P>
<P>
This is caused by an increase in the average international tea
price from 1.5 U.S. Dollars per kg in January to 1.8 Dollars in
June, due to the crop's failure in neighbouring Kenya, one of the
world's major tea producers, which produced over 250 million
kgs last year.
</P>
<P>
An increased overall production as a result of additional
acreage by especially those estates recently repossessed and
rehabilitated by Asians also accounts for the growth.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's tea output had increased from 12 million kg in 1993
to 70 million kg last year due to a series of economic reform
measures such as the liberalization in tea industry and the
handing over of tea estates to the Asians who controlled more
than 70 percent the industry before 1973 and were expelled by
Uganda's former administration in 1972. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Take Steps to Promote Energy and Road  Construction Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 12 (Xinhua) -- India is to take steps to
speed up the development of the country's power, petroleum and
roads, which are playing more important role in economic
development, a government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Union cabinet has decided to issue an ordinance to enable
companies in the power, petroleum and road sectors to adopt the
straight-line method to calculate depreciation under the
Income-Tax Act. The adoption of the straight-line method is
expected to provide an incentive to the upcoming power plants, the
refineries in the petroleum sector as well as road construction
projects, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The ordinance will ensure an average depreciation rate thereby
increasing profits for the companies in the initial years. Since
the infrastructure sectors are allowed a five-year tax relief in
the initial years, higher profits with no tax liability would come
as an incentive for the companies involved. The return rate on
investment is thus likely to appreciate significantly in the
initial years, he further said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
