<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Tamil Rebels to Continue Attacks on Ships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Tamil rebels who
have so far attacked three foreign vessels since July have
threatened to continue attacks on foreign ships sailing in Sri
Lankan territorial waters, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have informed Colombo-based foreign missions and
other sources that they will attack vessels on shipping lines
found in "Tamil territorial waters."
</P>
<P>
They cautioned that any vessels, foreign-owned or otherwise,
which were engaged in activities associated with the Sri Lankan
military will be considered legitimate targets.
</P>
<P>
The warning was issued from the rebel's international
headquarters in London on Wednesday, one day after the Tamil
rebels attacked the vessel "Cordiality" which was registered in
Panama and owned by a Chinese company based in Hong Kong. The
vessel was on a mission to transport 30,000 tons of illuminate
sands for an American buyer.
</P>
<P>
On July 15 they threatened to attack ships transporting
supplies to security forces in the North. A few days later the
rebels' navy, the sea tigers, seized the North Korean ship MO Rang
Bong off the Northern coast.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
