<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Funds Used For Relics Conservation In Shaanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Shaanxi
province, home of the world-famous terra cotta warriors, has used
more than 6 million US dollars of foreign capital over the past
five years for its protection and conservation of historical
relics.
</P>
<P>
The Shaanxi Archeology Institute used 400,000 Deutsche mark
from a German Museum grant to establish a cultural relics
restoration center. The two sides have also cooperated in research
of the Xi"an's terra cotta warriors and horses, according to a
local official source.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government donated 3.8 million US dollars for the
construction of China's first center for the comprehensive
restoration of cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO and the Japanese government recently provided 2.5
million US dollars for conservation of the Daming Palace built in
Tang Dynasty (618-907 A.D.).
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi, the capital of 14 feudal dynasties over a period of
more than 1,100 years, is abundant in cultural relics and
historical sites.
</P>
<P>
The province has 55 historical sites under state protection and
provincial museums house over 56,000 pieces of cultural
relics, leading all provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities of the country in terms of the number of rare
cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, the province has spared no efforts in
strengthening exchanges with overseas cultural relics protection
departments. It sponsored 60 exhibitions of historical relics in
some 20 countries and regions, including Germany, France, Japan,
the United States, and Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan. Those
exhibitions attracted a total of well over 25 million visitors.
</P>
<P>
The province also hosted five international symposiums on
research and protection of cultural relics during the period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Single School Curricula Proposed for East Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Harmonization of
school curricular and certification in Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda
by March next year has been proposed by senior education and
cultural officers of the three east African countries.
</P>
<P>
This is part of recommendations made by the officials at the
end of a three-day meeting under the auspices of the East African
Cooperation (EAC) secretariat on Thursday in Arusha, northern
Tanzania, according to a news dispatch available here today.
</P>
<P>
It was also agreed at the meeting on the establishment of
equivalent entry points at each level of education and production
of teaching materials.
</P>
<P>
The three countries will also exchange staff and examiners for
university programs and compare standards of curricula and degree
programs.
</P>
<P>
It was also recommended at the meeting that distance education
be revitalized and encouraged to develop adult learning in the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda are making efforts in integrating
various domains for economic and social developments in eastern
Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
