<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Textile Ministry to Further Relax Imports Limits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 12 (XINHUA) -- India's Union Textile
Ministry is open to phasing out import restrictions on several
textile items at the earliest, the ministry sources said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Excepting some items such as apparel, garments and processed
fabrics where India has a slight disadvantage in technology, it
can phase out most of the other import restrictions in the textile
sector in a short period of time, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
India has imposed quantitative restrictions on 600 textile and
garment items.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Textile Ministry will seek to move
towards tariff protection which is allowed under the World Trade
Organization (WTO) norms. The peak duty which can be imposed on
items is between 40 to 50 percent, the same sources said.
</P>
<P>
Western countries are pressurizing India to phase out consumer
goods imports restrictions within 2-3 years while India has
insisted on seven years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
