<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Backs Financial Sector Reform in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today
approved a loan of 15 million U.S. dollars to Thailand to help the
country reform its financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The loan, which is offered for the Financial Implementation
Assistance Project, will be used to assist the Thai government
improve the structure, resiliency, and soundness of the financial
sector and to address the immediate need to determine the future
of suspended finance companies.
</P>
<P>
The project is part of a broad effort supporting the
stabilization and structural adjustment program the country has
undertaken to restore sustainable levels of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
It will complement the standby facility provided by the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and will underpin the World
Bank's contribution of 1.5 billion dollars to the emergency
financing package from bilateral and multilateral sources.
</P>
<P>
The project, with a total cost of about 22 million dollars, is
aimed at reducing the costs of the financial sector restructuring
program. It aims to do this through design of policies and
institutional arrangements to resolve the future of the suspended
finance companies quickly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
