<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Head Sees Asia as The Economic Giant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- As Asia becomes increasingly
important in the international scene, the United States and Asia
must work together, Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region Tung Chee-Hwa said here tonight.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a dinner hosted by the Economic Club of New York,
Tung said Asia's economic and political impact on the world in the
decades to come cannot be overlooked and "must be seen in a
favorable manner by the United States."
</P>
<P>
Asia may well emerge as the world's largest producer, capital
lender and capital borrower, as well as the world`s largest
consumer market, he said. "The growth of Asia's economy is good
for everyone."
</P>
<P>
Tung forecast that Asia could have an economy larger than the
North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) countries or the
European Union (EU) in the next century.
</P>
<P>
"The region, already well known for its high savings rate,
could produce 1200 billion to 1300 billion U.S. dollars in
additional annual savings than it does today, thereby becoming one
of the largest capital markets in the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tung is here on his first U.S. trip since he took the top post
in Hong Kong since China resumed the exercise of sovereignty over
the region on July 1. He arrived in Washington Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tung reiterated his confidence in Hong Kong's future -- because
of the Chinese government's commitments to make the "one country,
two systems" policy a successful reality.
</P>
<P>
Touching on close U.S.-Hong Kong business links, Tung said the
U.S. stood as Hong Kong's second largest trade partner in 1996
while Hong Kong was the 11th largest export market for the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The United States put nearly 14 billion dollars of investment
into Hong Kong, its third largest investment destination in Asia
and Pacific after Japan and Australia, Tung said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
