<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Set Up Wood-Based Industrial Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is planning to
establish two international-level wood-based industrial zones in
the capital Yangon to boost the manufacture of value-added
finished wood products in an effort to stop the exports of teak
and other wood logs.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Minister for Forestry Lt. Gen. Chit Swe on Thursday
urged local manufacturers to make good use of teak, hardwood and
other lesser-used species in penetrating the world market, the
official newspaper the New Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
He said more and more foreign entrepreneurs have turned towards
Myanmar for raw wood and production of value-added finished wood
products is being carried out with foreign investments and
technical know-how.
</P>
<P>
He said Myanmar will also undertake, in cooperation with the
International Tropical Timber Organization (ITTO), the project for
introducing Myanmar's lesser-used timber species to the world
market and the project for upgrading production efficiency in
furniture manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's hardwood export in the 1996-97 fiscal year ending
March was valued at 147,800 cubic tons, while the export of teak
at 138,700 cubic tons.
</P>
<P>
The country's export of forest products amounted to 218 million
U.S. dollars in the 1996-97, accounting for 24.4 percent of the
total export, second only to the export of agricultural products,
according to the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar restricts export of logs and bans the private sector
from exporting teak logs after the enactment of the country's
Forest Law in 1992. However, export of value-added wood products
is encouraged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
