<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Crew to Return Home Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-two Chinese sailors of
the vessel Cordiality, which was attacked and damaged by Tamil
rebels, will fly back to China soon, a Chinese diplomat said
today.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Hui, one of the two Chinese diplomats sent to meet the
crew of the ship following Tuesday's incident, told Xinhua in a
telephone interview at Habarana this morning that 22 of those
saved crew members will return home as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
He added that the other five that survived the attack,
including the captain, chief mate, second mate and two other
sailors, will return to Pulmoddai to look after the damaged ship.
</P>
<P>
The tragic incident took place off the Pulmoddai coast in
Trincomalee District at 1:30 am Tuesday. A total of 32 Chinese
sailors were on board the ship, which was loading ilmenite sands
and scheduled to set sail 24 hours later.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan troops rescued 27 of the crew members, but the other
five were missing. Those rescued were transferred to Habarana, a
small town 80 kilometers southwest of Trincomalee, late on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said the 22 sailors will arrive in Colombo today prior to
their departure for home.
</P>
<P>
The engine room of the vessel was severely damaged after it
caught fire in the attack. A charred body was found on the vessel,
by the side of which was a handgun. The identity of the body was
not known yet.
</P>
<P>
Among those missing, one was from Hong Kong and the other four
were from China's inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side has asked the International Committee of the
Red Cross (ICRC) to contact with the rebels with regarding to the
recovery of those missing.
</P>
<P>
The Cordiality was the biggest foreign vessel attacked so far
by the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), which is fighting
for a separate state in the north and east of Sri Lanka.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
