<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Dam Resettlement Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, September 12 (Xinhua) -- By early September, some
26,000 residents have moved from areas in central China's
Hubei Province which will be inundated when the Three Gorges Dam
on the the Yangtze River starts locking in early November.
</P>
<P>
The figure accounts for 85 percent of the total 28,200 residents
who will be relocated before November, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Dam will store water in three stages.
Completion of the dam will mainly inundate Yichang, Zigui,
Xingshan and Badong counties in Hubei Province, as well as two
county seats and nine towns. A total of 44 factories will also be
relocated.
</P>
<P>
Provincial government's assistance will enable some 8,000 of a
total 8,800 farmers move into new residential quarters. The
reconstruction of new county seats for Zigui, Badong and
Xingshan counties is proceeding smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Dam will prevent flooding on the Yangtze and
will have an annual power output of 84.7 billion kwh. The entire
project will be completed in 17 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
