<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea, Japan Fail to Agree in Fishery Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 12 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and Japan failed to
narrow their differences over rewriting a 1965 bilateral fisheries
accord at a two-day meeting here Thursday, local media said today.
</P>
<P>
During the fifth round of fishery talks this year, the two
sides put forward their respective proposals and made no major
differences in their positions, according to Shin Jung-seung,
South Korea's chief delegate to the talks.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean delegation reaffirmed that it will consider a
provisional settlement only on condition its sovereign claim to
the Tokto islets (Takeshima islets in Japanese) not be affected
and existing rights for its fishermen be fully guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese side repeated a demand that Tokyo and Seoul work
out a temporary fisheries agreement before they draw the
boundaries of their 200-nautical-mile exclusive economic zone.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese version of a revised accord, which proposes joint
management of the seas around the Tokto islets, was unacceptable
to South Korea, the chief delegate said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of the two countries will continue to discuss
the issue at the United Nations in late September, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
