<HEADLINE> United States Denies Trying to Divide Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Thomas McLarty, an
envoy of United States President Bill Clinton, has denied that his
country wants the division of Latin American countries.
</P>
<P>
"The American hemisphere must work unitedly with the United
States on a basis of confidence and mutual respect," McLarty said
in an interview published today by the Brazilian daily, Gazeta
Mercantil.
</P>
<P>
"The United States does not want to separate or divide the
Latin American countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
McLarty is in Sao Paulo to attend the Third Southern Common
Market (Mercosur) Economic Meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said the Clinton administration was worried about the claims
that Washington intended to divide the continent with different
foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
These policies included the lifting of the embargo on the sale
of U.S. arms to Latin America and granting Argentina the status of
an ally of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
The envoy said Brazil was "a crucial ally" of the United States
and Chile could buy U.S. combat planes after the ban on the sale
of arms to Latin America was lifted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
