<HEADLINE> Asian, European Finance Ministers to Meet in Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Finance ministers of the
Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) participating countries will meet here
next week to exchange views on the financial and currency
situations in Asia and Europe, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Asia is expected to obtain European promises to extend more
capital to finance the region's infrastructure needs at the
gathering of 25 ASEM finance ministers.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also discuss ways to strengthen their
customs cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Thai officials said Thailand will take the opportunity to
clarify its economic standing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin on International Situation, China's Foreign Policy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Party General Secretary Jiang
Zemin reiterated here today that China is a staunch force for
safeguarding world peace and regional stability and its
development poses no threat to any other country.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the 15th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China which opened here today, Jiang Zemin stressed that
China needs a long-term peaceful international environment, and
above all, good relations with the surrounding countries for
carrying out the socialist modernization program. "China will
never seek hegemony even when it becomes developed in future," he
stressed, adding that the Chinese people, for a long time
subjected to aggression, oppression and humiliation by foreign
powers, will never inflict these sufferings upon others.
</P>
<P>
He said that the present international situation as a whole is
becoming more relaxed and peace and development are the main
themes of the present era. "The trend toward multipolarity has
further developed globally or regionally in the political,
economic and other fields. World forces are experiencing a new
split and realignment," he noted, adding that the development of
the trend toward multipolarity contributes to world peace,
stability and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
For a fairly long period of time to come, it will be possible
to avert a new world war and secure a favorable, peaceful
international environment and maintain good relations with the
surrounding countries, Jiang Zemin said.
</P>
<P>
However, the cold war mentality still exists, and hegemonism
and power politics continue to be the main source of threat to
world peace and stability, he pointed out. "The unjust and
irrational old international economic order is still infringing
upon the interests of developing countries, and the gap in wealth
is widening. It is still serious that human rights and other
issues are used to interfere in the internal affairs of other
countries. Local conflicts due to ethnic, religious and
territorial factors crop up from time to time. The world is not
yet tranquil."
</P>
<P>
It is necessary to adhere to the ideas of Deng Xiaoping about
diplomatic work and firmly pursue an independent foreign policy of
peace, Jiang said. In international affairs, he noted, "we should
determine our position and policies by proceeding from the
fundamental interests of the people of China and other countries
and judging each case on its own merits. We shall not yield to any
outside pressure or enter into alliance with any big power or
group of countries, nor shall we establish any military bloc, join
in the arms race or seek military expansion."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin on International Situation, China's Foreign Policy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"We oppose hegemonism and safeguard world peace," Jiang Zemin
declared. "We do not impose our social system and ideology upon
others, nor will we allow other countries to force theirs upon
us."
</P>
<P>
He said that China will work to bring about a just and rational
new international political and economic order.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary to respect the diversity of the world, Jiang
Zemin said. "All countries are entitled to choose the social
systems, development strategies and lifestyles that suit their own
conditions."
</P>
<P>
Jiang stressed the continuity of the good-neighborly policy,
saying that "this has been our consistent stand and will never
change."
</P>
<P>
The Party general secretary promised to further strengthen
China's solidarity and cooperation with the Third World countries
and further improve and develop China's relations with developed
countries on the basis of the Five Principles of Peaceful
Coexistence. "All countries should respect each other and live
together in amity regardless of their differences in social
systems and ideologies," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin said that China will conduct extensive trade,
economic and technological cooperation and scientific and cultural
exchanges with all countries and regions to promote common
development by persisting in the principle of equality and mutual
benefit; China will take an active part in multilateral diplomatic
activities and give full play to China's role in the United
Nations and other international organizations; and China will
develop new types of inter-party relations of exchange and
cooperation with all political parties of various countries which
are ready to have contacts with the Chinese Communist Party with a
view to promoting state relations on the basis of the principles
of independence, complete equality, mutual respect and
non-interference in each other's internal affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
