<HEADLINE> Philippine President Calls for Wider Cooperation With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos said here today his country wants to develop political and
economic ties with Russia and does not rule out cooperation in
military technologies.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the ITAR-TASS news agency, Ramos said the
two nations' defense authorities are in "positive negotiations" on
military collaboration.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, arrived here earlier today on a two-day official visit,
was scheduled to hold meetings with his Russian counterpart, Boris
Yeltsin, and Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and sign a number
of documents.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the State Institute of International Relations
in Moscow, Ramos said the Philippines hopes that Russia would be
more involved in political and economic affairs in the
Asia-Pacific region, including in the security affairs in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Grigori Karasin said today that
Ramos' visit will be of major significane to bilateral ties as
well as Moscow's relations with the Association of South-East
Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Ramos also delivered a speech at the Russian
Council of Industry and Commerce, calling for more Russian
investment in the Philippines. 
</P>
