<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Romanian Joint Communique (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu's state visit to China, which ended today, will
make important and positive contributions to the continued
development of friendship and cooperation between China and
Romania, according to a communique issued by the two countries
today.
</P>
<P>
The communique said that the presidents of the two countries
held fruitful talks, and reached wide-ranging consensus during
exchanges of views on the growth of bilateral ties and on
international issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
During the September 8-12 visit, the two sides signed a
cultural cooperation plan covering the period 1997-2000, an
agreement on environmental protection, a convention on cooperation
in the sanitary veterinary field and animal quarantines and health,
and a document on cooperation between trade promotion
organizations in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The communique said the two countries enjoy a time-honored
friendship, and are satisfied with the smooth development of
friendly and cooperative bilateral relations, which have been
forged in spite of the changing international situation and their
respective changes and reforms.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that the people of the two countries share
a common desire to promote long-term, stable and close cooperation
in all areas, and that such cooperation will not only serve the
fundamental interests of the two countries, but will also benefit
peace and development in both Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
The communique pointed out that close bilateral cooperation is
based on universely-recognized basic norms for the international law,
including mutual respect for national independence, sovereignty
and territorial integrity, equality and mutual benefit, and mutual
noninterference in internal affairs of another country.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed to expand political dialogues,
including those at high levels, and support the contacts between their
respective governments, parliaments, nongovernmental
organizations and local authorities in order to enhance mutual
understanding and promote mutually beneficial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The communique also noted that the two countries regard the
expansion of economic and trade cooperation as an important goal
for developing the Sino-Romanian relationship.
</P>
<P>
The two sides support direct contacts between companies,
enterprises and traders in the two countries in order to promote
trade ties and engage in cooperation in new industrial and
technological projects, in accordance with their respective
potential and possibilities.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will continue to encourage cooperation in the
market of a third country, as well as in the financial and and
banking sector.
</P>
<P>
The communique said the two countries will continue to support
bilateral cooperation in scientific research, technological
development, environmental protection, culture, arts, education,
journalism, tourism and sports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Romanian Joint Communique (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The communique said the two countries reiterated respect
for their respective choices of roads for social and economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side understands and respects Romania's choice to
integrate with the Euro-Atlantic structure, and appreciates its
policy for continuing cooperation with all other countries,
including countries in the Asia-Pacific region. China
also places high value on Romania's role in and contributions to
safeguarding peace in central and eastern Europe, and in Europe
and the World at large.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian side reiterated that it recognizes that there is
only one China in the world, that Taiwan is an inseparable part of
China, and that the government of the People's Republic is the
sole legal government representing the whole of China.
</P>
<P>
Romania appreciates China's role in and contributions to
maintaining peace and security in Asia and in the world as a
whole, and places high value on China's independent foreign policy
of peace.
</P>
<P>
The communique pointed out that the two countries fully
support the expansion of the role the United Nations is playing in
keeping pace in regions and the world, promoting the common
development of all nations and solving problems facing mankind
through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will increase consultations on international
issues of common concern and will work closely together in the
battle against international terrorism, organized crime, illegal
drug trafficking and arms sales, and in maintaining world peace
and stability.
</P>
<P>
The joint communique was signed by President Jiang and
President Constantinescu following talks on September 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
