<HEADLINE> Italy Wants Speedup in Euro Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 10 (Xinhua) -- Italy, once viewed as one of the
countries having trouble meeting the single currency criteria, is
urging a speedup in the preliminaries leading to the move.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Dini wants the list of the first
wave of countries to join the union be drawn up earlier than
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
He said at the end of a two-day summit with his Spanish
counterpart, Jose Maria Aznar, that it would be better to decide
on the first wave "as soon as possible" to prevent uncertainty
unleasing market turbulence.
</P>
<P>
Which countries will be among the first wave to adopt the
single currency, known as "Euro", will be decided next May, when
all the countries' final fiscal figures for 1997 ared due.
</P>
<P>
"The final date for setting the list of participants in the
single currency is May. But the sooner we decide on it, the
better," Prodi told a news conference held with Aznar after their
meeting in the central northern Italian city of Bologna.
</P>
<P>
In the first day of their meeting, Prodi and Aznar renewed
their resolve to respect the criteria and timetables of the Euro,
to be launched on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Italy and Spain had been considered two countries which had
more difficulty in meeting the budget deficit and inflation
requirements necessary to qualify for the single currency.
</P>
<P>
To qualify, countries must lower their budget deficit to three
percent of gross domestic product (GDP), and their public debt to
60 percent of GDP. Their inflation rates have not to be more than
1.5 percentage points higher than the average figure of the three
best performing countries.
</P>
<P>
However, Italy has managed to bring down its deficit and
inflation through austerity policies and fiscal reforms.
</P>
<P>
Italy's deficit-GDP ratio, estimated to stand at 3.2 percent by
the end of 1997, is expected to drop to 3 percent in 1998, the
Internation Monetary Fund said earlier. Its inflation had lowered
to 1.5 percent in August, the lowest since the Spring of 1969,
said Italy's national statistics institute, Istat.
</P>
<P>
In Spain, Aznar's government has taken similar measures to cut
public spending. These included a 1.5 billion U.S. dollar cut in
spending, a reduction of government posts and a wage freeze for
all public servants in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Its inflation in March dropped to 2.2 percent, the lowest in 29
years. A European Union report expected its public deficit to
fall to three percent in 1997 from 4.4 percent in 1996 and 6.6
percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Also topping the annual Italy-Spain summit was reform of the
the 15-member European Union's Council of Ministers and more say
for foreign ministers in decision-making in the bloc.
</P>
<P>
Italian diplomats said Italy was determined to make sure that
key reforms -- blocked at the EU summit in Amsterdam in June --
were implemented between the scheduled launch of the single
currency in 1999 and the end of enlargement talks early next
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Votes for Clinton's Tests Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate today
overwhelmingly approved President Bill Clinton's plan for national
reading and math tests as a measure to upgrade U.S. school
learning.
</P>
<P>
But the Senate's approval followed an agreement on handing
control of testing to the National Assessment Governing Board, an
independent board created by the Congress to run existing tests
known as the National Assessment of Educational Progress.
</P>
<P>
The tests, to start in March 1999, would measure fourth-graders
for their reading ability and eighth-graders for their ability to
do math.
</P>
<P>
The 90-minute tests would be based on fixed standards of what
children should know and be able to do in those two core subjects.
Other achievement tests commonly measure students against a
shifting norm, or average.
</P>
<P>
"The measure they have embraced will help parents ensure their
children have mastered the basics of reading and math," Clinton
said today, hailing his victory in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
"This is another example of what can happen when people of good
will of both parties... look to the future and not to the past,"
Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the testing proposal
"took a major step forward today, and we believe it will prevail
in the end."
</P>
<P>
However, a House vote was put off until Tuesday because of slow
movement on a massive spending bill.
</P>
<P>
The tests plan will face House opposition by conservatives who
argued that the tests would threaten local control of what
children should learn. Liberals also were against the plan, saying
the tests would be used to further brand low-achieving students
from impoverished school districts as inferior. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
