<HEADLINE> Czech Republic Economic Growth Slowdown in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Czech Republic Prime Minister
Vaclav Klaus told a seminar of American entrepreneurs Thursday
that the growth of the country's gross domestic product in 1997 is
expected to be 1.5 to 2 percent, less than half the former target.
</P>
<P>
Economic authorities here said this will be the lowest growth
in the recent three years.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic has been faced with huge financial and
foreign trade deficits this year and more than one-third of
enterprises are now losing money. The government was forced to
institute tight credit policies twice, in April and May.
</P>
<P>
The country's economic difficulties worsened in July when
catastrophic floods hit eastern areas and caused losses of
hundreds of millions dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic's economic recovery began from 1994. After
consecutive decrease of 14.2, 6.4 and 0.9 percent from 1991 to
1993, the country's gross domestic product rose 4.8 and 4.4
percent in 1995 and 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
