<HEADLINE> Italian Experts Predicts Lower Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Italian experts have predicted
that the country's inflation, measured by the consumer price
index, will fall to 1.4 percent in September from 1.5 percent in
August, with a chance of falling to as low as 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Inflation remains under control and appears to have weathered
the super-dollar," the ANSA news agency quoted Paolo Casadio, a
macro-economist for the Credito Italiano bank, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Casadio said he did not believe this summer's hike in the value
of the U.S. will effect consumer prices in Italy.
</P>
<P>
Analyses show prices stable in all sectors, including fuels,
with prices for farm goods falling and no increases expected for
clothing, health care, entertainment, hotels and furniture.
</P>
<P>
This would indicate a monthly increase in the consumer price
index of 0.2 percent which would bring down the 12-month rate to
1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Forecasts from the Confindustria studies center also saw
inflation declining to 1.3-1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
ANSA quoted other Italian experts as saying that prices are
expected to remain stable for the rest of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
