<HEADLINE> Motorola (China) to Expand Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Motorola (China) Co. of the
United States plans to have 65 percent of its parts turned out in
China by the end of 2002 as part of its localization program for
China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese-produced parts currently account for 50 percent of the
company's total production volume. For example, the Tianjin-based
Shuanglu Group which manufacturers chains for Motorola beepers has
an annual production value of 80 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the Tianjin-based Motorola (China) Company, which
commenced operations in 1992, ordered parts valued at 270 million
US dollars from 130 manufacturers in 51 Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
Another 600 Chinese enterprises provided indirect products and
services valued at 213 million US dollars to the company.
</P>
<P>
Motorola (China) also exports products from Chinese suppliers
to other Motorola facilities oversea. It expects this year's
exports to double last year's figure of 80 million US
dollars. according to the local manager. 
</P>
</TEXT>
