<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine: More Talk Than Action in Fighting Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Corruption is now widely viewed
as a real threat to the normal functioning of the Ukrainian
government although talk about graft and efforts to stop it have
been going the rounds of the East European country for some time.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe Ukraine must resort to harsher measures since
official corruption is not just a major disruption at home. The
world community directly ties credit allocations to how
effectively the government battles the problem.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian law on state service provides law enforcement
agencies with more control over officials. The three-year-old law
calls for all officials to take an oath of loyalty to the state
before starting their service.
</P>
<P>
"Yet the law is hardly ever applied in practice," says Maxim
Shendryk, who heads the anti-corruption department of the Ministry
of Internal Affairs (MIA).
</P>
<P>
"Officials simply do everything they can to avoid taking this
oath," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to avoiding their oath of office, some officials
are often very reluctant to declare their incomes.
</P>
<P>
Gennady Lelikov, who chairs the main state services department,
says that only 92 percent of officials in national agencies
submitted income declarations.
</P>
<P>
The worst violators in this area appeared in the Defense and
Justice Ministries, Lelikov said.
</P>
<P>
He said the anti-corruption law stipulates that information on
incomes, securities, real estate and bank deposits of cabinet
members and their relatives must be published in the official
media. This rarely happens.
</P>
<P>
"By itself, declaring income is not the answer," says Valery
Ratsiuk, deputy head of the MIA Organized Crime Division. "Since
there's no developed mechanism for registering incomes and
expenses of individuals at present."
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma has determined to improve the
image of his country through sweeping away corrupt officials. He
set up the National Bureau of Investigation in April to monitor
how officials comply with laws, but corruption cases are rarely
launched against top officials.
</P>
<P>
Local media cited the most telling example that involved former
Acting Prime Minister Yukhym Zviagilsky, who fled to Europe and
then Israel after being charged with abuse of power and
graft. Zviagilsky returned to Kiev this March claiming innocence,
but authorities appeared to have done nothing to close the case.
</P>
<P>
There has not been a single high-profile case against a top
official in this former Soviet republic, though there are many
instances where officials use their power to take advantage of
business deals, Lelikov noted.
</P>
<P>
He expressed pessimism over the present situation, and
said: "Corruption looms large in the Ukrainian society, everybody
talks about it but refuses to take any real action for fear of
confronting big bosses." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin Reviews Past and Looks into New Century (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- In the first decade to come,
China will establish a more or less ideal socialist market
economy, and by the middle of the next century the modernization
program will have been accomplished by and large and China will
have become a prosperous, strong, democratic and culturally
advanced socialist country, said Jiang Zemin here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 15th National Party Congress which opened this
morning, Jiang, general secretary of the Communist Party of China
(CPC) Central Committee, said earth-shaking changes have taken
place in China over the past century from 1900 when the
Eight-Power Allied Forces occupied Beijing, subjecting the Chinese
nation to great humiliation and bringing the country to the verge
of subjugation, to the year 2000 when China will enjoy a fairly
comfortable life on the basis of socialism and take big strides
toward the goal of being prosperous and strong.
</P>
<P>
He said the past century has witnessed the Chinese people
undergoing three tremendous historic changes on their road of
advance and the birth of Sun Yat-sen, Mao Zedong and Deng
Xiaoping, three great men who stood at the forefront of the times.
</P>
<P>
The first change, he said, was represented by the Revolution of
1911, which overthrew the autocratic monarchy reigning in China
for thousands of years. Led by Dr. Sun Yat-sen, the revolution
pioneered the national and democratic revolution in the true sense
in modern times.
</P>
<P>
The second change, Jiang said, was marked by the founding of
the People's Republic of China and the establishment of the
socialist system. This was accomplished after the founding of the
Communist Party of China and under the direction of the first
generation of collective leadership with Mao Zedong at the core.
</P>
<P>
"This was a great victory of the people's revolution which had
never been recorded in Chinese history, a great victory of global
significance for socialism and national liberation," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The third change, Jiang said, was featured by the reform,
opening up and the endeavor to achieve socialist modernization. It
was a new revolution initiated by the second generation of
collective leadership with Deng Xiaoping at the core.
</P>
<P>
The conclusion drawn from the great changes over the past
century is as follows: Only the Communist Party of China can lead
the Chinese people in achieving victories of national
independence, the people's liberation and socialism, pioneering
the road of building socialism with Chinese characteristics,
rejuvenating the nation, making the country prosperous and strong
and improving the people's well-being, he said.
</P>
<P>
When the world is heading toward the end of the 20th century,
Jiang said the CPC realizes that "the Party shoulders a lofty
historical responsibility for the destiny of the Chinese nation."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are the
major economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the
past few days:
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexican sorghum production, estimated at 4
million tons this year, will reduce 30 percent because of a
drought that affects several states of the country, said Urbano
Ortiz, president of the Mexican Sorghum Council.
</P>
<P>
Ortiz said that in Tamaulipas, the state that produces 70
percent of the national harvest, will have a drop of 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Panamanian merchant fleet has 13,717 ships,
that add up to 111.2 million gross registry tons, said Abraham
Sofer, the director of Consulates and Ships of the Finance and
Treasury Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The open registry of flagging of ships of Panama during the
first eight months of this year has collected 30.7 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil is expected to receive 20 billion
U.S. dollars in foreign investment this year, announced Carlos
Eduardo Moreira Ferreira, president of the Federation of
Industries of the State of Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in 1996 was 10 billion dollars, five times
more than in previous years.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica's coffee exports are expected to reach
400 million U.S. dollars this year, a 75 million dollar increase
over last year, said Guillermo Canet, executive director of the
Costa Rican Coffee Institute.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica will export 2.8 million quintals of coffee this
year, while the country will consume 300,000 quintals, said
Canet.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's foreign debt rose to 5.4 billion
U.S. dollars on July 31, said the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Of this amount, 23.535 billion dollars are medium and long term
debts and 1.449 billion dollars are short-term debts.
</P>
<P>
The total debt in the public sector rose to 5.4 billion dollars
while the debt in the private sector was 19.584 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay's food industries production increased by
13.74 percent during the second quarter of this year, over the
same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the Uruguayan Central Bank, tobacco, beverages,
and foodstuffs grew the most, which were 29.1, 18.5, and 13.7
percent, respectively, in the April-June period. 
</P>
