<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Pregnancies Declining in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The number of teens
getting pregnant in the United States has dropped significantly
since 1991, said Federal health officials.
</P>
<P>
The 12 percent drop for all girls nationally, comes after a
sharp rise in teen pregnancies during the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Vermont, with a 26.9-percent dip, led the country in recent
declines. Alaska followed with a 23.3-percent drop, and then came
Maine with a 22.7-percent decline. Texas witnessed the smallest
drop of 3.6-percent.
</P>
<P>
The information was released by the Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention (CDCP), in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
"This is the result of a lot of effort and a lot of education,"
CDCP researcher Stephanie Ventura was quoted as saying by the
United Press International.
</P>
<P>
Ventura says teen pregnancies peaked in 1991 with 62.1 births
per 1,000, after a 24 percent rise that began in 1981. The 1996
rate is 54.7 per 1,000. In 1996, an estimated 505,514 women under
20 gave birth in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
