<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Wins Asian Volleyball Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DOHA, Qatar, September 11 (Xinhua) -- China won its first Asian
title in 18 years after beating Japan 3-1 in the Asian Men's
Volleyball Championship here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese team last won the Asian title in 1979. Since then,
the Chinese spikers had won several Asian Games titles but could
not match their Japanese and South Korean counterparts in the
Asian Championships.
</P>
<P>
In the last match of the single round-robin finals on Thursday,
the Chinese spikers played a high-spirited game by taking the
first set 15-12 after 40 minutes' fierce fighting.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese team took advantage of tight blocking in the first
set and forced the Japanese team into a handful of errors.
</P>
<P>
But the Chinese team suddenly lost their rhythm of attacking
and blocking in the second set and enabled the Japanese to come
back into the game and win the set 15-8.
</P>
<P>
The third set saw the Chinese team in total control again.
Enjoying an advantage in height and blocking, the Chinese team
surged ahead 2-1 with a 15-7 victory.
</P>
<P>
In the fourth set, the Japanese team fought desperatly and once
led 9-6.
</P>
<P>
But the Chinese spikers never gave up and staged a superb
come-back by taking 8 points in a row to take a 14-9 lead.
</P>
<P>
The usually steady Japanese team collapsed and though they
narrowed the gap to 10-14 they could not stop their Chinese
opponents from winning the match point and claiming the title
15-10.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese team dropped only one set in their five outings at
the championship.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, Australia beat Chinese Taipei 3-0 to take
the bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
Twice Asian champions South Korea finished only fifth. It is
the first time that South Korea failed to enter the top four in
the history of Asian Championships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
