<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Croats Agree to Participate in Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The main Bosnian Croat party
agreed late today to participate in local elections in Bosnia
after two days of intense negotiations with international envoys
here.
</P>
<P>
The discussions, and mounting pressure on Croatian President
Franjo Tudjman, came after the Bosnian wing of the Croatian
Democratic Union (HDZ) threatened earlier this week to boycott the
first polls since the Bosnian war ended in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The HDZ accused the rules for the elections, scheduled for this
weekend, of being unfair. They insisted that voter registration
had put Croat voters at a disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE),
which is organizing the voting, said it would make some "agreed
corrections."
</P>
<P>
OSCE envoys met Tudjman and Bosnian Croat representatives for
three hours and hammered out an agreement just before midnight.
</P>
<P>
Kresimir Zubak, the Croat member of Bosnia's three-man
collective presidency, said all the most important issues had been
solved.
</P>
<P>
Now that the Bosnian Serbs have also dropped their threat to
boycott the polls, all three main nationalist parties in Bosnia
will take part in the elections on Saturday and Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
