<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Identify Previously Unknown Dinosaur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
identified a previously unknown dinosaur from fossils found in
northeast China's Liaoning province, today's "China Daily"
reports.
</P>
<P>
The fossils, unearthed in late 1995 and show a row of
feather-like structures runing from the animals' head to its
tail. Some scientists thus thought that they belonged to an
ancient ancestor of modern birds, possibly pre-dating the
Archaeopteryx.
</P>
<P>
The find was initially named Sinosauropterys", meaning "China
lizard wing", the paper says.
</P>
<P>
However, a group of scientists from Nanjing and Beijing made a
conclusion that the fossils are of a new species of small
dinosaur, similar to the compsagnathus, a dinosaur whose remains
are found in America.
</P>
<P>
They found that the creature had ten cervical vertebrae, 13
back vertebrae and 50 tail vertebrae. Its tail was twice as long
as the body. And it was possibly a meat-eating dinosaur, the paper
says.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that further scientific study was needed to
clarify the feather-like structure and function, according to the
paper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0301 </DOCNO>
