<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Bank Profits Up 5.8 Percent in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Profits at U.S. commercial
banks increased to a record 14.6 billion dollars in the second
quarter despite hefty losses on credit-card loans, the U.S.
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. (FDIC) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Boosted by the strong economy, the profits in the U.S. banking
industry jumped by 5.8 percent in the second quarter from 13.8
billion dollars in the same period of 1996,
</P>
<P>
FDIC Chairman Andrew Hove said the strong performance resulted
mainly from a surge in lending growth, especially for commercial
and industrial loans.
</P>
<P>
"We have enjoyed 18 consecutive quarters -- four-and-a-half
years -- where quarterly profits have exceeded 10 billion dollars,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the record rate of losses on credit cards in
the second quarter continued to parallel the high level of
personal bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
Losses on credit-card loans accounted for two-thirds of all
loan losses reported by commercial banks during the quarter,
according to the FDIC, which supervises savings and loans in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Banks declared as uncollectible an annualized 5.22 percent of
credit card balances in the second quarter, up from 4.48 percent a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
It is the highest quarterly rate for credit-card loans in the
14 years that banks have reported such data, the FDIC said.
</P>
<P>
The losses have been especially hard on banks that specialize
in credit-card lending. Of the 74 such institutions in the U.S.,
35 reported declining income in the second quarter, the FDIC said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mali Qualifies for U-17 Quarter-finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Mali secured a quarter-final
seat at the Under-17 World Soccer Championship after crushing its
strong opponent Mexico 3-1 in a fierce fight here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two Group B teams, each with 4 points in stock, played a
game of life and death since the kickoff and staged ominous
attacks in front of the other's net.
</P>
<P>
Sega Diakite opened the account for Mali in the 39th minute,
slipping the ball into the net in a melee in the penalty area.
Five minutes into the second half, Seydou Keita added another
goal.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to reverse its misfortune, Mexico went all out on
counter-attacks. In the 63th minute, Luis Ernesto Perez Gomez
converted a short pass.
</P>
<P>
Six minutes before time, Keita, taking advantage of a 12-yard
kick, scored the second goal for Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Spain, which has already qualified for the quarter-finals in
Group B, routed New Zealand 5-0 in Ismailia, the Egyptian Suez
Canal city.
</P>
<P>
Oman and Brazil, both had booked a seat in the last eight,
determined their placing in Group C in the last match played in
Alexandria. Brazil took the upper hand by defeating Oman 3-1.
</P>
<P>
Both out of the race for the championship, the U.S. embarassed
Austria 4-0 in a face-saving match in Port Said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
With the last four group matches played Thursday, Spain, Mali,
Brazil and Oman joined Germany, Egypt of Group A and Ghana and
Argentina of Group D to enter the last eight.
</P>
<P>
The teams will take a rest on Friday and Saturday. Brazil
will face Argentina, Germany confronts Mali on September 14th
while Ghana plays Oman and Spain meets Egypt on 15th. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
