<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group Preliminaries End at Euro Volleyball Tourney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Olympic champions and hosts
the Netherlands have lived up to their reputation by leading the
round-robin group preliminaries that ended Thursday at the
European men's volleyball championship.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch did not drop a single set en route to winning all
their outings in group B. They blanked Bulgaria in their fifth
and last outing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands will next meet world league titlists Italy in
Saturday's semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
The Italians were squeezed into second place in group A as they
lost their second-round tie 3-0 to Yugoslavia that went on to lead
the group preliminaries.
</P>
<P>
Both Italy and Yugoslavia scored four wins against one defeat
with a similar tally of sets won and lost in the six-team group
preliminaries. Yugoslavia topped the team standing due to its
victory over Italy.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia play France in the other semi-final tie.
</P>
<P>
France stole the day's highlight in a dramatic qualifying match
with Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
The French spikers won the first two sets 15-13, 15-8 but
conceded the ensuing two sets 10-15, 3-15, setting up a
tiebreaking fifth set.
</P>
<P>
In the decisive set in which each winning play counted toward a
point no matter which team was serving, the Ukrainians led the
French up till 8-6 when they changed ends of court.
</P>
<P>
Two wild smashes betrayed Ukraine of its lead and the two sides
went from 9-9 to 16-16, tying the set six times before deadlocking
at 17-each.
</P>
<P>
An unforced error at serve cost the Ukrainians dearly again
while the French turned the odds of serving in the tiebreaker into
a killing smash to seal the set and the match away from their
opponents at 19-17. The match took three hours and a half to
finish.
</P>
<P>
In the day's other matches, Italy beat Russia 3-0; Slovakia
defeated Greece 3-1 while Yugoslavia downed Germany in straight
sets all in group A.
</P>
<P>
Group B actions saw the Czech Republic labor heavily before
defeating winless Finland three sets to two.
</P>
<P>
Like the semi-finals that dramatically paired off the reigning
Olympic champions with the world league titlists, the playoffs for
fifth through eighth places were to be full of drama as Slovakia
is due to play the Czech Republic while Ukraine duo with Russia.
</P>
<P>
Slovakia and the Czech Republic had been one country while
Ukraine and Russia had both been former republics of the Soviet
Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
