<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Represents New Market of Next Millennium, Banker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TORONTO, September 11 (Xinhua) -- China's economy offers
extraordinary opportunities for business and represents the "new
market of the next millennium," a Canadian banker said here today.
</P>
<P>
Matthew W. Barrett, chairman and chief executive officer of
Bank of Montreal, made the remarks in a speech to the Canada-China
Business Council and the Hong Kong-Canada Business Association
luncheon.
</P>
<P>
"China, the new market of the next millennium, engages us all
-- as individuals, as citizens of the international community, and
as corporate executives," he said.
</P>
<P>
Twenty years ago, China amounted to "a little more than a vast
planned, subsistence economy". Deng Xiaoping's reforms has
transformed the country.
</P>
<P>
"Today, China is richer and freer than at any time in its
modern history," Barrett noted.
</P>
<P>
He highlighted China's tremendous economic growth:
</P>
<P>
-- China has seen an average real growth since 1980 of just
about 10 percent. In the past five years, it has been closer to an
average of 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- In the past four years, inflation has fallen from 25 percent
to 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- China has become a trade giant, with trade 290 billion U.S.
dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
-- China has absorbed nearly 200 billion U.S. dollars in
foreign investment, and is second only to the United States as a
destination for foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
-- And most important, millions of Chinese have shaken off
poverty.
</P>
<P>
Barrett said he has been to China on a regular basis during the
past few years. "Yet so great is the pace of change that I feel I
am arriving in a different place each time."
</P>
<P>
"During the last 20 years, China has generated more growth for
more people in a shorter time than any other period in history.
</P>
<P>
"Bank of Montreal, which is dedicated to serving the growing
international needs of its clients, refuses to be immune to such a
mega-trend in world history," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Bank of Montreal, the third largest
commercial bank of Canada, opened a new branch in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
It became the first Canadian bank and the third North American
bank to open a full branch in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Barrett announced today that the bank's board of directors will
meet in Beijing on September 29.
</P>
<P>
"This will be the first time, in 180 years, that our board has
met outside the North American continent," he said.
</P>
<P>
The board meeting in Beijing represents the bank's strategic
interest in China, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Promote UN Reform at 52nd General Assembly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The Permanent
Representative of the United States to the United Nations, Bill
Richardson, pledged here today that the U.S. would promote a
comprehensive reform of the world body at the forthcoming U.N.
General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Richardson told reporters at a press briefing that the
principal priorities and goals of the United States for the 52nd
U.N. General Assembly is to push forward the U.N. reform
momentum.
</P>
<P>
The 52nd U.N. General Assembly is scheduled to open on
September 16 at the U.N. headquarters in New York. Dozens of heads
of States and Governments as wells high representatives from 185
member states are expected to come here to express their opinions
about current world situations and development of the world body.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said that he believed the U.N.'s core mission in the
years ahead should be focused on issues of peace and security,
sustainable development, humanitarian response and social
progress.
</P>
<P>
"Reform momentum is now part of UN culture," the U.S.
Representative said while voicing full support to U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
Annan put forward a comprehensive U.N. reform plan in mid-July,
including a cut of U.N. regular budget and personnel in the
Secretariat as well as a new post of Deputy U.N.
Secretary-General.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said that Annan's reform efforts starting earlier in
the year had already improved the U.N.'s financial and personnel
management, strengthened oversight and enhanced the Secretariat's
effectiveness and efficiency in carrying out intergovernmental
mandate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno: Anti-Crime Legislation Help Reduce Crime Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Crime rates have kept
dropping since President Bill Clinton signed landmark anti-crime
legislation three years ago, Attorney General Janet Reno said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Federal, state and local authorities used the law to toughen
enforcement, strengthen punishment and fight violence against
women, Reno said.
</P>
<P>
The federal government has handed out enough three-year grants
to pay for placing 65,000 more police officers on the nation's
streets, she added.
</P>
<P>
Republicans in Congress have said Americans owe more thanks to
changing demographics than to the anti-crime bill. They contend
crime remains much too high, and experts have said the
administration is reaping the benefit of a baby boomer generation
mellowed with age.
</P>
<P>
However, Reno said that more work needs to be done, especially
on ways to prevent and deal with youth violence.
</P>
<P>
"It is now important that we build on our progress though
continued cooperation with state and local enforcement and through
the development of prevention programs that can give our
youngsters a chance for a strong and positive future," she said.
</P>
<P>
Reno has urged Congress to alter juvenile justice bills being
debated in Congress. She said the bills focus too heavily on
getting tough with teen-agers, not enough on after-school programs
that keep potential offenders occupied.
</P>
<P>
Clinton signed the crime bill September 13, 1994, promising to
give local communities enough money to put more than 100,000
additional officers on the nation's streets by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
