<DOCNO> XIE19970912.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Epidemic Slow-down in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The deadly epidemic of
AIDS is slowing down in the United States as it was no longer No.
one killer of the nation's young and middle-age adults, said a
desease control center today.
</P>
<P>
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said today that
a 26 percent drop overall in the rate of AIDS deaths between 1995
and 1996 placed the desease to the second leading cause of death
for people between 25 and 44 in the nation.
</P>
<P>
Accidents, such as falls and car crashes, are the leading cause
of death for the group that accounts for more than half the
nation's workforce. Cancer is No. 3, the CDC said.
</P>
<P>
The AIDS death rate in 1996 fell to 11.6 deaths per 100,000
people, down 26 percent from a rate of 15.6 the previous year, the
CDC said. For adults between 25 and 44, the rate fell to 27.2
deaths from a rate of 36.9 in 1995. In 1994, the rate was 36.7 in
that age group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
