<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Reaches 2-Month Low Against Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar hit a
two-month low against the mark Thursday as traders turned to the
German currency after a report that Japan's economy shrank sharply
in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
With Germany's economy expanding, traders boosted the mark to a
nearly three-month high against the yen, in turn pushing the
dollar lower against the mark.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar settled at 1.7805 marks,
down from 1.7990 late Wednesday, and its lowest level since July
11. The dollar is down about 6 percent since reaching an
eight-year high against the mark on August 6.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also was quoted at 119.55 yen, up from 119.31.
</P>
<P>
Other dollar rates in New York, compared with the previous
session, the dollar were lower against Swiss francs, French
francs, Italian lire, but up against Canadian dollar.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6015 U.S. dollars, up from
1.5850 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
