<HEADLINE> Race Commission Chairman Calls Task "Daunting" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Historian John Hope
Franklin Thursday pledged to involve every segment of the American
people in a searching examination of the nation's racial
divisions.
</P>
<P>
Franklin, who was appointed by U.S. President Bill Clinton to
head the Commission on Race Relations, said, the effort will
"penetrate every area of American life that has been permeated by
race," Franklin said at a panel discussion on race and racism
sponsored by the Congressional Black Caucus Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The aim is to forge "a respectful relationship of one person to
another and one race to another so we can hold ourselves up as a
beacon light of equality, freedom and justice for all," he said.
</P>
<P>
But he described his task as the "most daunting and fearsome
task" he had even undertaken with trepidation.
</P>
<P>
Franklin was addressing the panel discussion attended by a
mostly black audience at the University of the District of
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
"For more than 350 years this country has lived with, tolerated
and even accelerated racial injustice," Franklin said.
</P>
<P>
Another speaker, Professor Cornell West of African-American
studies at Harvard University, said that "white supremacy still
saturates and permeates every nook and cranny of American life."
</P>
<P>
Representative John Lewis, a Democrat of Georgia, said the time
has come for a return to nonviolent protest to curb what he said
are attempts to roll back civil rights gains, including
affirmative action to help minorities.
</P>
<P>
"There are powerful forces seeking to undo the progress we have
made," he said. "It is up to us to speak up and speak out, to
organize and to agitate for what is right."  
</P>
</TEXT>
