<HEADLINE> Tung Says China's Development Poses No Threats to Others </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 11 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee-hwa, Chief
Executive of China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR), stressed here today that China's development poses no
threat to any other country in the world.
</P>
<P>
"The growth of China's economy is good for everyone," Tung said
at a luncheon hosted by the Asian Society and other three
organizations including The Hong Kong Economic &AMP; Trade Office in
New York.
</P>
<P>
"Larger markets with a broader range of needs for goods and
services provide opportunities to the world at large," the Chief
Executive said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that China needs social stability at home and
"China also needs stability and peace in Asia and around the
world."
</P>
<P>
"Like many other developing nations, the strengthening of the
military is not a tool for expansion but a declaration of
independence and a political statement to the international
audience, especially for China after 156 years of humiliation,"
said Tung who flew in here last night during a four-day visit to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive is scheduled to meet U.S. President Bill
Clinton at the White House on Friday before leaving for home.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the China-U.S. economic relations, Tung said that
he believed the two nations "are not competitors."
</P>
<P>
"On the contrary, there is much room for China and the U.S. to
become complementary economic systems, which could generate
enormous benefits to both parties," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Tung stressed that Sino-US relations based on mutual trust,
respect and understanding is an important element for Hong Kong's
success.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that there is much synergy between China and the US.
I hope that we will all one day recognize the potential of a
strong Sino-American partnership," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
